animal.description:
**Please read her entire bio before requesting an application**
**We are only looking to place her in a home with an existing dog**

At roughly 8 years old, sweet Mama is a mature lady. Mama is an incredibly shy pup who is looking for a special and patient family. She is timid and skittish, and will take some time to warm up. When that time comes, she will then decide to stick to your side - a "velcro" dog if you will who is incredibly connected and loyal.

Once she warms up, she absolutely loves to cuddle with her person. Her couch potato side strikes a nice balance with her desire to be an adventure girl. She get so excited to go for walks and is a great little co-pilot. You should see how this little monkey lights up when the leash comes out - she gets SO excited to go on walks and seems to particularly love the beach. 

With a careful feeding regimen, she has been slowly losing weight. Mama is very food-driven! She has done well around bigger dogs, and she currently lives with two dogs who are  medium and large in size. She interacts well with dogs of all sizes during our walks - she is a pretty confident dog towards other dogs, despite her size.

We are looking to place Mama in a home with an existing confident pup as she seems to gain much confidence from being around another dog. This makes her more comfortable which is beautiful to see and why we are wanting to make sure she finds a home with another pup. Again, it is important that she goes to a quieter home with people who understand that she will not approach strangers upon first meeting and she takes time to warm up. 

If you are interested in this sweet girl, please email us at adoptions@pawfund.org to request an application.

Hey, everyone! I bet you are wondering how I got my name, Skipper Dipper. Well, just ask my foster mom. She will tell you that I literally skip, hop and jump when I am excited! I am a very playful pup with a huge personality and am also a very friendly guy. Playing with my toys is really great, and also I love playing with my people. I am totally awesome at playing fetch! I just love to play with my folks or my canine buddies! I learn new games easily because I am so smart, and I am very eager to please my people. She tells everyone how adorable my ears are and that they just add to my goofy personality. I wonder why they didn't just name me Goofy.

I am an affectionate fellow and also mild mannered. I always listen to my foster mom and go in my kennel when she tells me to. I also have a great time with her whenever we get to go on a car ride. Yippee! Riding in the car is awesome! I really want my people to love me! When I get my forever family, I will be the most devoted, loveable and faithful companion ever. I can't wait!

Zara is pretty girl and a great dog who was picked up as a stray. Zara was very frightened at the shelter and didn't want to be restrained, and was afraid of men. Zara has been in a foster/boarding home for two months now and the family has earned her trust, including the husband https://youtu.be/MtpwBkJD_tQ Zara is all smiles these days. Her only issue is she does not like to be restrained, but we think with time she will trust her new owner if they stay kind and patient with her. Earn her trust, like her foster did, and of course, peanut butter! Zara is super housetrained and she does not destroy anything. Zara is about 3 years old and weighs about 57 pounds. She tested well with other dogs, see her videos below, HOWEVER we have discovered she is VERY protective of food and toys so would be best as an only dog . We do stress Zara needs a dog savvy family and most of all a requires a patient owner. She is looking for a family to love her unconditionally. If you are interested in Zara please email Virginia virginiaz3@gmail.com When you email please be sure to add your phone number so she can call you back. We highly suggest no small children because of Zara's restraining issue. She tested heartworm negative and is current on her vaccines.

Zara has a buddy to play with, with her foster familyhttps://youtu.be/US7NmYUj9D8 Zara is in the red collar but very protective of food and bones which caused an issue so best as an only dog.

animal.description:
Bentley is by far one of the most loyal and loving companions to have around. Want to have fun, be lazy, be active? Bentley is all of that. This sweet dog will never disappoint, he's just so full of happiness! Bentley loves walks and car rides and being around other dogs and people! He truly is one of a kind!

Age: 9 y/o

Breed: Hound

Weight: 81 lbs

Experienced Handler Recommended: Bentley takes time choosing his people and trusting. Bentley is reserved and cautious until he is comfortable. And then he turns into Mr. Snugglepants.

Kid-friendly:
No small children

Dogs:
If other dogs, not super dominant, no small dogs

Cats: Not recommended due to high prey drive in hounds

Crate trained:
He is but doesn't need it.

Potty trained: Yep!

Likes:
He LOVES walks, lounging around, meeting new people!

Bentley would love a fellow dog to play with, a person who lets him sleep in the bed (or at least close) and a family who loves to walk, hike, and run. He is breathtakingly athletic and appears much younger than his listed age. His tail is powerful when he wags it, and he alerts you to everything the neighbors are up to with a deep bark. Bentley would love to have a companion, but we do recommend supervision during playtime with other dogs, especially males. He is not dominant but he's no pushover either. If he is adopted in an only dog home, we recommend he does have regular playtime with other dogs that are familiar friends. We also recommend giving Bentley "work" to do, as he breed is known to be a "working dog. He needs daily activity.

For multiple dogs, we also recommend considering crates when the animals are unattended for the safety and harmony of the pack. Bentley is reserved by nature which makes his integration into a new pack a slower process than some other dogs. He is not a social butterfly and must feel safe before he will integrate into the pack. Bentley's instinct is to mount other dogs, which is usually a sign of dominance, but with Bentley it is a behavior that was not corrected. We have been working on correcting it so that it happens less often, but with new people "alphas", new environment, new pack, Bentley is vulnerable to this behavior and other dogs. The primary key to success with Bentley is that he needs to trust his people first and foremost. He needs fairness in the pack and if he senses he is the second-rate citizen it may be hard. He has fear from his past and once he believes you have his back, he falls in love with you. Then he feels safe and secure with the whole pack.

Adoption fee: $375

Our dogs receive heartworm and flea/tick prevention the first week of each month, March through November. Dogs that have stage 3 or 4 dental disease will receive a dental procedure in rescue. We aspirate all lumps and remove those that our veterinary partners suggest removing.

Adopters will be responsible for continued preventatives, follow-up appointments, and medications (if applicable).

$50 discount for seniors (65+) and veterans. Adoption fees help pay for the dog's veterinary exam, vaccinations (rabies, distemper, and bordetella), HW test, blood panel, a microchip, and spay/neuter if needed and additional health needs specific to each animal.

You can apply to adopt at www.greyfacerescue.org/adoption-application

Better With Older Children  /  Last Weigh-in: 38.8 lbs

We were alerted to a pup that had been hanging around a local apartment complex for a long time but was not really interested in letting people get close. She had a thick human belt around her neck but clearly did not belong to anyone. When her medical condition began to physically deteriorate with BB gun wounds in her head and a very large growth hanging from her abdomen, we knew it was time to step in. 

After a few days of trying to earn her trust and the rescue of 3 other pups from the same area later (#sdfGraham #sdfHershey #sdfMarshmallow), we finally were able to humanely trap her and get her in to see our vet. And we are so happy she finally let us rescue her! 

Lil S’mores is definitely enjoying life off the streets. She’s a little shy at first, but she loves a good shoulder and back rub! And who can blame her after all she’s been through!?

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Tori is a very beautiful 3 year-old Husky mix female with a super-soft coat and gorgeous markings. She was surrendered to an overcrowded county dog shelter in late August by her owner who said she was not good with the toddler in the home. The child was pestering Tori and the parents thought Tori might snap at the toddler. We don't know how Tori was treated in her previous home but she will need a quiet home without small children-respectful teenagers should be OK. Tori has been very friendly and affectionate with all the people she's met since coming to us to work on finding the right forever home. She loves to have lots of attention lavished on her and enjoys being close to her human friends. The first few days she was with us, Tori seemed very uncomfortable around other dogs but now that she's settling in a little bit, she has relaxed and enjoyed meeting some fellow Canine Lifeline adoptables. Although she might be happy playing with dogs on occasion, Tori does need to be the only dog in the home as she does not like to share her things or people with other dogs. She walks very nicely on a leash and is looking forward to exploring her new neighborhood with her family. She has had excellent crate manners in her foster home and is likely to be housetrained although we can't guarantee that she won't have a few accidents in her new home as she adjusts to the new routine. Her pretty long coat will require regular brushing to keep her looking and feeling her best. Tori was adopted from us shortly after her arrival but recently returned because her family found that she did not like cats so Tori will need a kitty-free home. Being a Husky mix, Tori seeks out affection on her own terms and isn't always comfortable with being hugged. She would do best with an owner who understands the breed and can give Tori the space she needs. Tori also needs a home with a yard that has a secure aboveground fence (no invisible fence) to keep her safe at home. Tori weighs about 30 pounds and her adoption fee is $325. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Tori. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Tori and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Courtesy Post for Mona's House Animal Rescue

Mozzy is a big, goofy bully mix.  He loves everyone and has a lot of energy.  He is just 1 year old and 65-70 pounds.   He is very food motivated and eager to please, but is in need of basic training and manners.  He is not a couch potato and will need someone willing to work with him to make him into the gentleman he can be.  He is currently working on leash walking and basic manners. 

Mozzy has a lot of love to give.  Small children may be knocked over because he doesn't know how big he is.  He is dog friendly but any potential canine siblings would require a meet and greet.  He is good with cats.  Mozzy is neutered, up to date on vaccines and routine care and is microchipped. 

If you would like to meet this big, happy boy, please contact Elena by phone, text or email. 860-857-2270/elena.rogan.cecil@gmail.com  He is being fostered in Groton, CT.

animal.description:
*ADOPT ME!*
Beaux - 10 years old, located in Pennsylvania
Dog ID#: 191051-P-D-LA
Intake Date: 09/06/2020
Available Date: 10/10/2020 

Hi, my name is Beaux!  I grew up in the south hunting with my original Dad, but after a separation I went to live with my Mom for a while.  In 2016, I was diagnosed with Cutaneous hemangiosarcoma. I developed some really gross things that grew all over me (tumors) and Mom couldn’t help me anymore, so an amazing family in Massachusetts took me in and got me all the care I needed and guess what!? My cancer is now in remission. 

 I really loved living with my new family but after one of my procedures I started being sensitive to loud noises.  Being in a noisy city environment was not the best for me anymore so I got to take a ride to a quiet neighborhood in Pennsylvania.  At first, I wasn’t sure what to make of things.  I picked a whole Queen size bed to sleep in on my first night and my new foster family said it could be mine while I was here.  I slowly started to learn that the noises that I was always expecting before are no longer there, but the resident dogs help comfort me if I still get scared. I really love to lounge around and go on walks with the other dogs. Sometimes I pull when I’m on a leash but it is just because there are so many new things to smell!  I’ve been getting really good at following the other dogs’ lead and realizing that when I pull, we stop walking.  My ideal forever home would be someplace quiet with at least one other dog.  I like to run around and play with a Jolly Ball and other outdoor toys, so a fenced in yard would be perfect… and if you have some bunnies, squirrels or birds for me to chase and look at that would be even better!

Since you have gotten this far in my bio, I should let you know that I would be best in a home as an only dog.  I am very friendly and love people and kids, but I don’t really enjoy the company of other dogs. I am currently coexisting with he other dogs in my foster home and don’t mind walking past strange dogs outside, but if I had my way I’d prefer to have my people all to myself! The two resident dogs I am living with have been very calm and patient about getting to know me and because they are keeping a respectful distance, I am slowly getting more confident around them. I do not want to hurt other dogs, but they make me tense and I don’t like it when they get in my face. We go for pack walks together daily and I have no problem passing other neighborhood dogs and walking beside my canine pals. I think that’s because there are more interesting sights and smells to think about. It is inside where I feel too confined around other dogs, but my foster family is working on helping me get better with this. In addition, I am too excited by birds and cats to calmly live with them.

Beaux is an English Pointer that will be 10 years old, up to date on all shots, neutered, microchipped and negative for heartworms.   He is on monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventative.  Beaux is afraid of any loud noises (thunderstorms, fireworks, etc.) and is also afraid of big trucks, but only when outside.  If a UPS/FedEx truck pulls up while he is inside, he does not seem to be bothered.  When he gets scared, he will pant, shake and either pace the house or freeze in place.  He also appears to show some fear even when it’s just raining with no thunder. If you put him in a covered crate and administer some trazadone it seems to help. He is a great sleeper during the day and at night.  He will not sleep in bed with you for the whole night but will lay there for a few hours before finding a spot of his own.   He LOVES to be outside in our fenced yard running around and looking for any kind of critter but if he will be outside in the sun all day does need to wear UV shirts to protect his skin. 

Want to learn more about one of the dogs we have up for adoption? Fill out our adoption application (http://www.pointerrescue.org/adopt.html)!!

TRANSPORT AVAILABLE TO APPROVED HOMES! (currently within 600 miles)

*good with dogs and cats
*fully blind

What Queen Ester's foster mom has to say about Queen Ester:
Queen Esther loves to do her part to keep everyone smiling! She loves her walks and gets excited when she hears me getting the leashes out. She also LOVES belly rubs! She doesn’t play with toys so much, but she gets excited when she hears her foster sister play with a toy. Then she’ll try to play with her. 
Esther currently sleeps in her bed in her own room. She has a dog bed and a big fluffy comforter I folded for her. She knows what I’m saying when I say time for bed.
She is a silly silly girl. She does try to climb in my lap and she seems to always find her way on the couch when I’m not looking. ? She is a happy go lucky girl and most people don’t even realize she’s blind. 
She’s been really good with big and small dogs. She doesn’t like being bullied but is good about giving a mama dog “arf!” to say knock it off already after it’s becoming obnoxious. And then all is forgiven. I really don’t think she would be happy as an only dog. She likes dogs and cats both!

animal.description:
The world of rescue can be full of surprises. Sometimes you plan on rescuing one pup. Just that one pup. And then you end up with s’more pups.  

Graham started off very subdued but has started to come out of his shell and is quite perky. It just took him a minute to realize what we tell every new streetdog- "The worst is over, it just gets better from here!" Hershey didn't need any convincing at all. She knew she was moving up to the good life! Little Marshmallow must have never had a good night's sleep because all she wants to do is to curl up in your lap and snooze! 

All three pups are approximately 10 months (October 2020) old and, despite tough circumstances, are so very sweet and generous with kisses! They all seem to really enjoy the company of other pups too! Hershey definitely has the most energy and enthusiasm. Graham is happy, grateful, and medium energy level. Little Marshmallow is perfectly content to bat her pretty white eyelashes and curl up for a nap anywhere she can find, as long as she is touching you!

We are so thankful that our s’more pups are as sweet as their names! And can’t wait for them to see and experience s’more of the good life! 

*Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

animal.description:
We've seen some pretty gals in our time, but Sophie might just take the cake! She's a beautiful 1 year old copper AmStaff gal with a bit of a lowrider build and a puppyish heart! Sophie arrived at CCR after being grazed by a car while running stray in the western suburbs. She wasn't seriously injured, but the incident slowed her down long enough for her to be caught! No one came forward to claim Sophie, and we're wondering if it's because her previous family wasn't all that nice to her. Sophie loves people but she's also initially pretty terrified that someone is going to hurt her...whether that's because she was hurt previously or because she was never interacted with much at all, we don't know. What we do know is that if you go slow, give Sophie time to adjust and lots of sweet talk, she'll open up and then all bets are off! Unfortunately, Sophie seems to have a particular fear of men, so we are looking for a female-only household for Sophie. Sophie adores other dogs and really needs a home with another playful dog that will wrestle with her and also show her that people are good and she can be brave! Because of her initial skittishness, Sophie needs an adult home with no children that has a little patience to let her go at her own pace. Sophie is super affectionate and presents initially very submissively...but don't let that fool you! This lady has lots of rough and rowdy play that she'd like to let loose! So if you have a playful dog, an adult home, and lots of love to give...Sophie's your gal!

To meet Sophie, please submit an application at chicagocaninerescue.org!

animal.description:
Greetings, my dear! I’m Chi Chi, a well-mannered older gentleman, looking for a place to spend my golden years. I’m a nine-pound, nine-year-old chihuahua mix, fully vetted, neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and on heartworm preventative. 

Some call me a charmer, and I don’t deny it! My soft, plush fur is like a velvet jacket, and you’ll love it when I cuddle up to you or cover you with kisses. Speaking of kisses, mine are extra gentle since I’m missing all but two teeth. My tongue may loll out of my mouth a bit, but, trust me, it only adds to my adorableness! And don’t think that because of my senior status I just lie around all day. I enjoy playing with toys and other dogs and would love to have a dog companion to share my occasional bursts of energy. Of course, I’d be happy as an only dog too; humans are my favorite companions. Be prepared for a happy little shadow when you adopt me!

I’m a softspoken fellow, and I’ll whimper softly to let you know I need something like dinner or another cuddle. I do suffer a bit of arthritis, so I need to take regular medication and be held and picked up gently. It doesn’t keep me from enjoying a leisurely stroll around the neighborhood though; I’m great on a leash! I’m accustomed to using puppy pads for taking care of my business. Leave one or two in discrete locations, and I will use them reliably. I’m also used to dining in my crate, but I’d prefer not to spend a lot of time in it, nor do I need to, since I am very respectful of my human’s property. 

At my age, it’s hard to be starting over and in search of a home. I thought my last home was my forever home, and I don’t understand why I was given up. Would you give this old dog a chance to learn some new tricks in your family? There’s a lot of life and love left in me!

If you are interested in adopting Chi Chi, please DO NOT SEND A MESSAGE TO OUR RESCUE GROUP.  We are too busy placing dogs in great homes to answer messages and inquiries through the listing site.  

PLEASE GO TO THE LINK BELOW TO COMPLETE AN ADOPTION APPLICATION.
 
www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application
 
CRT requires an approved adoption application and a home visit for all adoption applicants.  CRT transports to OH, KY, IL, MI, MN, WI.

animal.description:
Earl is an amazing little guy. He is about 2 years old and 43 pounds, which makes him the perfect medium size. His green eyes are mesmerizing as he pays close attention to his surroundings, and his expressive eyebrows, pink nose, and fluffy tail wrap up the one of the kind package for this tender hearted guy. 
Earl had a rough start in life coming out of a hoarding situation in which he was not well cared for or socialized.  But dogs’ resilience is amazing and even though he thinks twice before trusting somebody, he is ready to put his past behind him.  He has been in an amazing foster home over the last 3 months and has made great strides in his socialization skills. He is fully leash, crate, and house trained and does great with other dogs.  He is still shy and nervous around new people, but has bonded with his foster mom, so we know he can trust given time and patience.
He loves snuggling on the couch, a soft bed, good food and going for walks. Most everything is a new experience for him so patience is vital. It will take time to earn his trust and affection but it’s so worth the extra effort. 
He would do best in a home setting that is quiet and calm. 
Please call 256-486-8770 for more information.

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE:
- REQUIRES ANOTHER DOG IN THE HOME
- NO SMALL DOGS
- EXPECTED TO BE A LARGE DOG

NAME: Ryan Reynolds

AGE/GENDER: Baby (born 7/29/2020), Male

BREED: Labrador Retriever and Australian Shepherd

ADOPTION DONATION: $525

TEMPERAMENT: Playful and mischievous
WEIGHT: Estimated adult weight is 50-70 lbs.
HOUSE TRAINING: Not yet. He is a baby so he will need a consistent schedule with multiple opportunities daily to go outside while he works on it. Puppies should not be considered reliable in regard to house training until 6-12 months of age. They're a lot like toddlers, who require diapers. He is developmentally delayed and taking a bit longer to potty train.
CRATE TRAINING: Good, he's young and trainable.
OTHER DOGS: Good and will need continued socialization, like all puppies. In fact, he requires another dog in the home to be a mentor to him. His mentor needs to be social and outgoing and have the patience of a saint since Ryan is very in your face. No small dogs as Ryan has a hard time adjusting his play style.
CATS: He's a bit of a cat chaser. Continued socialization will be important.
CHILDREN: Dog-respectful children, 12 and older

HEALTH: Ryan Reynolds is growing and learning every day, but he does have some developmental delays due to early trauma (see history below). Ryan Reynolds is still learning his name and how to track/look at his people when interacting with them. He has some lasting physical effects as well as mental effects, but he is a mobile guy. Prior to adoption, puppies will be altered, microchipped, flea treated, and dewormed. Puppies are given vaccination boosters in our care; however, adoptive families will be responsible for the remaining vaccinations that puppies need. Your adoption donation goes toward the cost of this vet care as well as transportation and general care costs.

HISTORY: Ryan Reynolds came to us after his mother attacked him and his litter mates. Thankfully Ryan Reynolds survived, but not without physical injury and subsequent developmental delays. Motley Zoo Animal Rescue was asked to find him a great forever family and that is exactly what we plan to do!

NOTES FROM FOSTER HOME: Ryan Reynolds is a puppy so he's playful and has a lot of puppy energy. He is super cute and fun, but a lot of work. His forever family should be committed to lots of training - obedience, house training, and socialization. This will ensure that Ryan Reynolds grows into a confident, well behaved adult. Due to his early trauma, Ryan Reynolds can be fearful and startle easily, especially when approached from over his head, so he would do best in a family with children 12 or older. A puppy's personality is dependent on their environment, and the structure and training they are given, in addition to socialization. Their personalities continue to grow and are shaped by their new adoptive families. Puppy daycare and socialization classes or puppy kindergarten are highly recommended for their personal development. He will more than reward you for all your hard work with lots of love, loyalty, and laughs.

Ryan is developmentally delayed and has some fear issues. However, with his brain trauma, he is behind mentally and is picking commands up slower than a puppy his age and even slower than his sister. He is learning his name and to sit. He is playful but skittish, which is why he requires older children in the home. Quick movements will send him running for cover. Even just touching him will startle him and cause him to scream and thrash in panic. As he is not your average puppy, he will need a lot of work, time and patience to build up his confidence. Neuro puppies tend to be hypersensitive so they tend to over exaggerate things/emotions. So fear can be intensified. He is very loving but not very cuddly and is just learning to snuggle. He is getting used to being held and hugged but can panic at being restrained (hugged) for too long. He is learning to walk on a leash. He is a wonderful silly and sweet little boy with just some little quirks.

All dogs adopted from Motley Zoo come with a leash and either a Martingale collar or a harness, depending on each dog's particular needs.

ABOUT MOTLEY ZOO

Welcome to Motley Zoo Animal Rescue. We are a 501(c)(3) non-profit animal rescue organization that is run entirely by volunteers. Motley Zoo does not have a brick and mortar shelter location. Instead, all our rescue animals are cared for in private foster homes where the animals receive one-on-one care and attention in a home environment until permanent placement is found. Please email adopt@motleyzoo.org and request an adoption application and we will work toward approving you as an adopter with our rescue so that we can set a time for you to meet!

For more information, please visit www.motleyzoo.org.

Thank you for considering adopting a dog in need!

Woof,

The Motley Zoo Crew

Text for more info: (724) 713-0458
Email with questions or to apply: adoptions@snarranimalrescue.org

Meet Wilson!

Let me tell you about my dude Wilson. He’s a simple country guy with simple country needs. He’s out here lookin’ for the farmer’s daughter and he ain’t about your high falootin’ city life.

Wilson’s a looker, he’s gonna turn all the girls heads with his beautiful coloring and perfect heeler build. But my guy, he knows that the prettiest lady out there is Mother Nature and he wants to share that with his new family. 

Wilson is not built for city life. Or suburban life. He wants land, he wants to explore, he wants to run and appreciate the beauty of the world. He also very much wants to please and help his human, so we believe the Wilson would love a farm and a job he could do. He’s been practicing his herding skills on some unappreciative cats, so he’s got what it takes and he’s willing to put in the reps to make it happen.  

Wilson does fine with other dogs, would probably like a friend around his size to ‘rassle and explore with, but most important to this guy is FAMILY. He wants one more than I’ve ever seen a dog want one and he wants so badly to be loved unconditionally. Wilson will give his life for his family, I have no doubt, so if you’re looking for LOYAL, you’ll never find another like this one. 

Wilson is vaccinated, neutered, current on heartworm and flea/tick prevention. He is housebroken and crate trained. He’s mostly good on a leash and has FANTASTIC recall off leash when hiking and exploring. He LOVES water. 

Are you Wilson’s forever family? Apply at www.snarranimalrescue.org

Meet Cooper! He's a lab mix, 6 yrs old and about 70 Lb. He loves to fetch and will bring the toy right back and drop it at your feet, ready to go again. He already has skills and knows sit, down and shake.
He previously lived with other dogs and has met several at the shelter. We have found that he's not a fan of the young ones who want to play and are in his face. Another dog that's calm would most likely be the best fit. Cooper needs a home without cats or chickens. He's house and crate trained. He does not like being swatted or hit as a form of correction.
Cooper is neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm negative and microchipped. His adoption fee is $150. Applications can be found on our website pcpoundpuppies.com
We also offer a 2 week trial adoption to make sure it's the right fit. We can loan you a crate during that time. He came to the shelter 10/2020***YOU MUST FILL OUT AN APPLICATION BEFORE WE DO ANY MEET AND GREETS. QUESTIONS? CONTACT pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com
Our adoption fee is $150 which covers a portion of the dog's vetting costs. The adoption process includes the completion of an application followed by an interview.
Click here to submit an adoption application: https://pcpoundpuppies.webs.com/adoption-application
***IMPORTANT: Due to the effects of COVID-19, our Sunday adoption events at Pet Food Center have been canceled until further notice. If there is a dog you are interested in meeting, be sure to contact us and we may be able to set up a meet and greet as soon as possible.***
You can get in touch with us by email at pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com or by phone at 812-483-4341 for more information.
We respond to inquiries and adoption applications at our earliest opportunity, but please be patient with us as we work full-time jobs and perform this service as volunteers. We do our best to return messages and schedule adoption interviews within a couple of days of receiving your application.
The fastest way to get the ball rolling is to complete an adoption application for the dog that caught your eye. Thank you for considering the adoption of a shelter dog!

Genny was found by animal control running in the rain with her buddy and then she sat in a shelter waiting for someone to save her. WSRH saved her, bathed her, got rid of the fleas and long nails, and got her to our vet for assessment. Genny has advanced heartworm disease and will visit with a specialist to determine the best options for treatment. Genny also has "cherry eye" which is an inflammation of the eyelid and has caused infection and severe dry eye, requiring daily eye drops.

As surgery is not an option for Genny at this time due to the heartworms, she is not yet available for adoption. Genny requires a foster (or foster-to-adopt) home that will give her all the love and care she deserves while following vet instructions and administering medications as directed.

If you are interested in fostering Genny, please review the adoption process and fill out the application on our website: www.wsrh.com

All dogs are available until “Adoption Pending” is noted next to their names. WSRH DOES NOT HAVE A PUBLIC SHELTER. ALL OF OUR DOGS ARE FOSTERED IN PRIVATE HOMES. Approved adopters only will be invited to meet the dogs.

This sweet adorable boy is making progress. We are so proud of he and his brother; they have had a long road but are learning life can be good to them. He is a petite dog, just the perfect size. He absolutely adores being outside. He loves to run and spin. He comes to the window when he is ready to come back inside. He is very sweet and quiet, does not make a lot of noise and loves his chew toys so that is a must! He is an overall sweetheart once he knows he is safe and feels comfortable. 

Bullwinkle came to us shy and timid. He will need someone who is patient and willing to help him with his insecurities; while he is making strides he will still need patience and time to acclimate. 

He will do best in a home with another dog that will help him build his confidence. He is about 35-45 lbs, almost 2 years old, loves salami, and his chew toys. He will need a home with a backyard since he is shy and the freedom of a yard allows him more time to come out of his shell. Older children who understand the need to go slow with him are recommended. 

All Dallas DogRRR adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon finalizing adoption. The standard minimum donation for puppies is $325 + 8.25% tax = $351.81, for dogs over 12 months the adoption fee is $225 + 8.25% tax = $243.66 and for our senior dogs 8 years and up is $100 + 8.25% tax = $108.25; this increase includes sales tax recently required by the State of Texas to collect. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. 

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process.

animal.description: Echo is a sweet and gentle loving boy, 3 years of age. He has never met a person he does not love.  He is a great house pet, enjoys belly rubs, snuggles and resting his head on your lap.  His favorite toy is the tennis ball though he will chew them up in time. Echo knows some basic commands (sit, kennel, and is working on down and stay). Since Echo is recovering from a spinal infection which had caused him some spine and neck pain, he will need extra work on leash walking, as he's been staying indoors most of the time.  He is starting to go out for short controlled walks  and has exhibited some reactivity to other dogs on walks, so will need some professional training with dog socialization and leash walking.  He is still on multiple medications which will be ongoing for a few months, and a follow up checkup is due in mid January to confirm his long term prognosis.  As Echo is loving to his people and wishes to please, good training and consistent practice following training should be a success.  His best fit home will include a private yard with sufficient fencing/gating (minimum 6 ft tall), experienced large breed dog owners, and a willingness to work through loving discipline to round out his already wonderful self. Older children over 14 in the home would be fine, and he should be the only pet. Echo has not been cat tested yet. He is crate trained.

animal.description:
Meet Lady Bug!

*Lady Bug is in our Houston foster program and will be able to travel in February.*

Hey everyone, I'm Lady Bug. I'm 9 years young and 53 pounds. I love humans and the attention I get from them, even kiddos! I haven't met kids younger than 5, but I do well with a little bit older ones. I love when I get head scratches, and back pets, and all the things from human that include attention, and I will seek it out. I'd much rather be around people than other animals, but I do get along with dogs that are my size, although it does take me a bit to get comfortable with them. I want to make my humans as happy as possible, so I'm working really hard on my potty training skills. Also, I know I'm a bit big, but I sure do love being a lap dog, where I can sit right next to you, real close, and snuggle when the time calls for it. I'm really hoping my new family likes to go on adventures and will take me with them! I have no issues with stairs, and hiking sounds like it would be super fun for me. I'd love getting to sniff all the things there are during a nice long walk, and it would burn a little of my energy. Maybe you have room in your home and can show and old gal what fun life can be?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
BeBe is a six year old pit bull mix. This, sweet happy go lucky girl is sure to brighten your day each and every morning.  She greets you with her ear to ear grin, an enthusiastic tail wag and an amazing little happy dance.  She looks forward to her walks and actually enjoys a little jogging.  At the end of the day, she's all about a soft bed, a good cuddle and perhaps some binge TV watching! BeBe came to us from a nearby shelter where she arrived as a stray with a pendulous mass hanging from her chest, which has since been removed. When she was spayed, two smaller mammary masses were also discovered and removed.  These masses were found to be cancerous so  should be monitored on a regular basis.  BeBe loves people, adults and older children alike. but wants to be your only four legged friend.   

The adoption Fee: $175 (dogs over 1 year) or $225 (dogs under 1 year) includes spay/neuter rabies, DHLPP and kennel cough vaccinations, worming, flea treatment, heartworm testing, heartworm preventative, microchipping and microchip registration fee.

To adopt during the COVID-19 pandemic please call us at 607-594-2255 ext 201 to schedule an appointment to meet her.

Or, visit us on line at www.schuylerhumane.org for additional information, an adoption application, to see more adoptable dogs and cats or for directions to our shelter.

animal.description:
Stella was not rescued from the streets of TJ by anyone. She rescued herself! One day Stella, a Black Lab mix, came to her rescuer’s office in TJ and just invited herself in. He had a welcoming home, so that was not a problem. Later that same day her owner came looking for her and took her home. Two days later the same thing happened, but this time she brought her friend Beethoven, a huge Saint Bernard. Again, no problem for her rescuer, but the same thing happened. At the end of the day, the owner came looking for them and took them home. The next day Stella came again, but this time did not allow the owner to take her home. When she heard his voice, she hid in her rescuer’s big warehouse. This procedure happened every day until the owner gave up. Stella definitely wanted to be rescued and find a different home!

She weighs 54 lbs., is around 7 years old but acts younger, and she plays like a puppy. Stella is good with most other dogs but can be a bit bossy. She has plenty of energy, she is housetrained, and she likes to go on a walk 2-3 times per day. She is a bit overweight at the moment and protective of her food, probably from her experiences in her former life. Her foster is working on slimming her down. She has only a few teeth left. Stella would do best in a home with no cats.

For more information, please call DANA at 760.519.5532 or jtnardi1@msn.com

Unable to adopt, but still want to help? Your support through tax-deductible donations are always needed and greatly appreciated! Donations go a long way in helping cover medical bills.

animal.description:
Achilles is a tri-colored 6 year old male foxhound-coonhound mix. He is approximately 45 pounds. He loves his people! We were told he was not good with other dogs. He is a very slender boy that would do well in a home that could help him gain some love weight.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

NOTE: This is a courtesy posting for another rescuer. Please do not contact ARRF, as we do not know this pet personally. To meet Suzy, see the contact information below.

Suzy is a spayed, 55lb grey female Bully mix estimated to be around 5 years old. This outgoing gal loves car rides despite having been hit by one right before she was rescued. Suzy is one of the special dogs that ARRF is featuring from a rescue partner in Tijuana, Mexico. 

Suzy was rescued off the street in TJ after Salvando Vidas, our rescue partner, saw her lying next to the road covered in blood. He was able to jump out of his car, scoop her up, and bring her to safety. Suzy had just been hit by a car and sustained a few broken toes and scrapes, but luckily turned out to be just fine!

Suzy is a great girl. She LOVES to go out, and every time Salvando grabs his car keys, Suzy is the first one standing by the front door. She jumps at the chance to go to the beach but likes to stay out of the water. Since she has a residual limp in one of her hind legs, Suzy is not the gal to take on long walks or runs. She would much rather sit next to you in the front seat of your car and enjoy the ride.

Suzy is house trained and gets along with adults and most dogs. Her caretaker thinks she would get along well with children, but probably not cats. Her vaccinations are almost all up to date. She will just need to get her rabies vaccine updated when she arrives in the US. As with all dogs from this rescue, Suzy has been treated for Ehrlichia and is dewormed regularly to ensure she is happy and healthy.

Unable to adopt, but still want to help? Your support through tax-deductible donations are always needed and greatly appreciated! Donations go a long way in helping cover medical bills.

To meet sweet Suzy, contact Dana, our ARRF representative working with the Tijuana rescue, at dkmikel@gmail.com or 760-519-5532.

animal.description:
NOTE: This is a courtesy posting for another rescuer. Please do not contact ARRF, as we do not know this pet personally. To meet this pet, see the contact information below.

Pinta is a 3-year-old spayed, black with white Terrier mix who weighs about 22 lbs. When her rescuers first saw Pinta she was strolling around a street market in Mexico with a HUGE tumor in her female parts. Although she was walking on 3 legs, it took almost an hour to catch her.

Pinta has had 7 chemotherapy treatments and reconstructive surgery. She is now cancer-free. Occasionally, when she is picked up by someone she doesn't feel 100% confortable with, she will have a "nervous pee." But if she is left with her 3 legs on the floor, she won't have an accident.

Pinta likes to be on her own and doesn't really like the company of other dogs--she basically just ignores them. We imagine she might find a cat as a companion more interesting. She loves attention and hugs but does not like to be picked up. We think an older caregiver would be perfect for her. Definitely not a girl that will go out for long hikes or running!

FOR MORE INFORMATION, PLEASE CONTACT DANA at jtnardi1@msn.com or call 760-519-5532. This pet is being fostered in the Carlsbad area of San Diego County.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name - Kona
Age - adult
Weight - 53
Other Dogs - Very friendly and playful with other dogs
Cats - likes our cat
Kids - good with kids in previous home
Background - pulled from a backyard breeder and quickly adopted. Unfortunately her adopted family moved and the kids lost interest, they felt it was in her best interest to be returned to ITP
Crate trained - quiet & relaxed in crate
Leash trained - walks pretty well on a slip leash for short distances or with a pack for longer walks. The pack gives her confidence to venture further from home. She is happy with short walks.
Housebroken - will go to the door when needs to potty
Eating habits - good eater, 2x's per day, dry with a little wet on top
Commands known - sit & off
Car rides - perfect passenger
Bath time - does great in the shower
Affectionate - snuggles and affection are new for this girl. Loves a good belly rub. She is learning what she likes
Activity level - moderate, bursts of energy, a quick zoomies or a short walk
Play style - will chase the ball for a few tosses, likes tug o war, loves chew bones
Bad habits - is a finger nibbler, a bit mouthy, working on it and it is improving, working on fear issues, takes awhile to warm up to new people
Redeeming qualities - super sweet and anxious to please, big heart
Best feature - soulful eyes, adorable little bowlegged tank

What Foster Mom wants you to know -
Kona is a super sweet girl who is learning what it's like to be in a loving home. She has overcome fear and trust issues and is starting to flourish. She loves being with her foster siblings and they have helped her to build her confidence. Kona is a squatty little tank,

so she is not going to be a big hiking or jogging companion. She likes a burst of play or short walk them a little nap. Her zoomies are hysterical and usually end with a roll and a mouthful of grass. She likes to play in the hose and her water bowl!

Please consider sponsoring Kona with either a one-time or monthly tax-deductible donation. Your donation will help It's The Pits with day-to-day care, including food, vaccinations, flea treatment, treats and toys. Click on the Sponsor This Pet link above to make your donation today. Thank you!
Complete an Adoption Application!

animal.description:
Loving, playful & affectionate, everyone meet our #Queen #WiggleButt Ms. #Nala. She's 4 years old, 55lbs, and an American Staffordshire Terrier mix. At the end of the day, Nala is honestly just the biggest lover that you'll ever meet. Nala craves human companionship, loves her daily walks, enjoys sunbathing in the backyard, lives for belly rubs, she's all about cuddles & movie nights & loves to give big kisses. She's 100% potty trained, 100% crate trained and does well on a leash.  Nala knows all of her basic commands and is very eager to please. The perfect family for Nala would be one that is active, loves the outdoors, an avid runner or someone who loves going on daily walks, and definitely a family that loves cuddles & puppy kisses.

When it comes to people, Nala loves everyone she meets! She loves & adores children and would make the perfect family pet. She'd do best in a home with kids over 10 years of age because at times she doesn't always understand her strength. Nala would thrive best as the only dog in her furever home, although she has made a few friends while in our care. Nala does not do well with female dogs,  but does well with submissive male dogs with a proper introduction. But once again, we would like her to be the only dog in her forever home. Nala absolutely adores the cat that is currently in her foster home- especially when it comes to cuddle time.

Adoption Requirements: No Exceptions
- Fenced in Yard Required
- Needs to be the ONLY DOG in her new home
- Nala would thrive best as the only dog in the home, but does do well with most submissive male dogs & does great with the male cat in her current foster home

Want To See More Pics:
https://www.petfinder.com/dog/nala-50060051/mi/ferndale/pro-pet-otic-foundation-mi1050/

Nala is currently up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue located in Metro Detroit. Her adoption fee is $150  & will include her distemper, rabies, bordetella, parvo, & lepto vaccines; deworming; microchip; heartworm test; fecal test & being fixed. Nala is currently on both flea & tick prevention and has had her ProHeart 6 Injection for heartworm prevention. 

***PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE POST & FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS****

Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue; previously known as the PRO-PET-OTIC Foundation, is a 100% Foster-Based Rescue that is ran by all Volunteers. Which means that we are not a shelter & each animal is in an actual home with a foster family. We kindly ask that you put any questions within the email & our team of Volunteers will get back to you. With the overwhelming amount of emails please be patient with our 100% volunteer family and we will get back to you. The application MUST BE filled out, a Vet Check MUST BE completed by our team, as well as a phone interview before we do a 'Meet N Greet.'
 
How To Apply:
If you're interested in adopting one of our available dogs:
1. Email LendingaHelpingPaw313@gmail.com with the dogs name as the subject when you ask for the adoption application.
2. Once you have completed the application, please print it out, fill it out, scan it, & then email it back to LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com. If you do not have a scanner, please take a picture with your phone and we kindly ask that you sent all attachments into one email.
3. Please make sure to call your vet to grant our organization permission to do a vet check on your current pet.
4. If you are interested in more than one dog, please list your top 3 choices on the completed application.
5. Please be honest & truthful on your application. We always do a vet Check. We always do a home visit. And we always have both the prospective families & dogs best interest at heart!

Thank you in advance for all of your love & support,
The Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue Family

Hazel is a little special needs in regards to eating. Since she has no teeth and no lower jaw she has to have soft food. Hazel loves being held and is a perfect little lap dog. She loves going outside and wandering in the yard with her foster mom and foster siblings. Being a senior, she is easy going and low maintenance. Anyone looking for a little companion to have as a cuddle bug, Hazel will be a perfect fit.

Hazel’s adoption fee includes:

Current vaccines 
Spay
Microchip 

To meet Hazel, we will need you to fill out an adoption application on our website www.preciouspalspetrescue.org.  If we feel you are a perfect match, we will contact you to set up a meet and greet.

Gender: Females

Dogs: Meet and Greet required
Housebroken: need frequent potty breaks due to age

Sis and Sister are a bonded pair. Sister is blind and Sis acts as her eyes and her protector! They came to us from Kentucky after their owner passed away, and they needed immediate medical care. They had skin infections, ear infections, and allergies. We have since taken care of these issues and have them on permanent lifelong allergy medications and diet modifications. They are in our de-stress living room where they enjoy the comfort of their own couch, their own tv with constant movies playing, and comfortable rugs to keep them off of the cement floors of the kennel. They enjoy the attention of the staff and volunteers alike. However, these special girls need a forever home. If you could open your heart to these angels, please fill out an application today!

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description: Introducing Stevie Wonder, a gentle, housebroken Labrador Retriever mix. Stevie Wonder, like his namesake, is blind, but that doesn't stop him from living a full life with lots of activity. Stevie is fine with other dogs and cats, and will fit into a home with other animals. Stevie does well when he is alone in the house. He simply takes his spot on his bed, near his toys and water, while he waits for you to come back from running your errands. Stevie, being blind, is careful where he walks in the house and prefers carpets to hard-surface floors. Stevie walks on a leash, but is a little skittish since he can't see where he's going and will need encouragement on his walks. Stevie loves being outside which is where his playfulness shines. He enjoys rolling in the grass. Once his feet touch the grass he is rolling around with joy, and he would do well in a home with a backyard that he can explore. Stevie is very mellow and well-mannered. He enjoys play time with other pets, but is not someone who needs a lot of attention. He likes belly rubs and scratches, and is very affectionate. He also loves a good chew toy, and a yummy treat. Stevie would do best in a home without stairs and with carpeting. A fenced-in backyard would be his dream! He does well alone, but would likely also do well with another furry companion to play with. As Stevie will take some time to adjust to his new surroundings, he would ideally love a pet-parent who has experience with blind dogs, or who has the patience to allow him to settle in. Are you the one who can give Stevie a safe home with lots of grass? Then come meet Stevie today!

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Brooke is a pretty 1 year-old Cattle Dog/Shepherd mix female who was surrendered to a county dog shelter along with her twin sister Brynn by their owner who could no longer care for them. These girls are beautiful dogs and are very outgoing and friendly but have had little training to date. Brooke does like to jump on people for attention but is responsive to correction and very food-motivated so is learning that all good things come to pups who keep their four paws on the floor. She is working on her leash manners and is pretty much all over the place at this point but with daily practice in her new home, will soon be walking like a pro on the leash. Brooke and her sister hated each other (sibling rivalry in full display!). We have found that Brooke is very particular about her dog friends so must be in the home as an only dog. She can also be very leash reactive when she sees other dogs so will need a home in a quiet neighborhood where she won't have to encounter new dogs on a daily basis. She also needs a cat-free home. Brooke has done well with crate-training in her foster home so we expect she'll pick up the house rules quickly in her new home. This girl has loads of potential and just needs a patient and active family who's got the time and energy to devote to molding a diamond in the rough into a canine good citizen. The reward will be years of love and devotion from this sweet girl. Brooke weighs about 45 pounds currently but is thin and needs to gain about 5 pounds to be at her ideal weight. Her adoption fee is $325. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Brooke. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Brooke and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Bacon is a 6 year old Lab mix who is need of a forever home but is currently looking for a foster home. 

Ideal Home: 
Balanced, physically strong, very structured, and very active home with an experienced large dog owner that either has experience working with food aggression/dominance or is willing to learn and work longterm on these issues - he is a highly trainable dog who may appear intimidating when aggravated or exhibiting dominant behavior. Example of training techniques an owner will need to be comfortable with: Hand feeding training (he is excited around food so this will likely be stressful in the beginning).   He can live with kids, but no younger than 15 until food aggression and dominance issues are under control. Can live with small or large dogs.
The rescues trainer will work with Bacon at your home. 

 fill out the application at this link: http://fs30.formsite.com/haarescue/adoptionapplication/index.html

Bulldog lovers take note! This guy is ALL THAT.

Sosa is a neutered male English Bulldog, who weighs about 67 lbs, and is between 4 and 5 years old. Sosa is a complex guy. He is picky about his male humans. He will do best in a female-only, adult home. He is working with a trainer, and potential adopters should be prepared to continue to work with him. He likes his crate, and is house trained. He's the quintessential work-in-progress!

Sosa is, for the most part, good with the other dogs. He is headstrong, so his new home will need to closely monitor interactions with other headstrong dogs. He loves his food and was very overweight. He was well over 70 lbs when surrendered, but has slowly been losing the excess weight. 

In typical bulldog fashion, Sosa has a lot of energy for a little while, but not a lot of stamina! He can be a bull in a China shop, then he easily wears out. He is good with people. He stands at the van and asks for help when trying to get in because his stocky body isn't able jump. He's a funny, quirky pup who can make a lot of noise, especially when he wants food. 

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
Yeager is a 5-year-old Shepherd mix. The people that found this boy wandering the streets could not locate his owners and fed him; they could not keep him because he can jump 4' fences.

Yeager is friendly and loves everyone. He is eager to please and even-tempered. He gets along fine with other non-reactive dogs. He will do best with older kids due to his size and his strength.

 We are working on basic commands. He is house-trained. He is calm but gets excited on a leash. He wants to be with his people and may whines  in his crate or when you leave. He is heartworm positive but no microfilaria. He was given a ProHeart 6 injection for slow kill. He is fully vetted, neutered and microchipped.

Please visit Regard4Life Animal Rescue at Petsmart in Longview on Saturdays for more information. You can also review our adoption album at http://Regard4Life.org or email regard4life.info@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Status - Adoption Pending

Meet Pongo.  He is 2.5 years old and is looking for his forever home.  He is a sweet and fun boy.  He is being fostered together with one of our other young male dalmatians. His Foster home reports:
"This 2-1/2 year old boy is full of vim and vigor. He is sure to steal your heart with hugs and kisses all day long. Pongo attaches very quickly to his humans, but needs very slow introductions to other dogs. He is currently fostered with another male dalmatian that is also looking for a forever home. His foster home also has a few dogs of their own and with slow proper introduction Pongo has done well with them.  He does love the girl dogs. He would probably do best living with another very playful female.  
He is the sweetest guy with one amber eye and the other a cool blue.  He loves his toys, the tougher the better as he chews on them constantly. He needs to be the only dog and in a home with no children under age 14. He doesn't play well with cats. 
Pongo will do best with a single person or a couple who will keep him actively entertained so that he doesn’t get bored, and who will take him to basic obedience classes. He has a soft little whine when he’s left alone, but it doesn’t last long.  He does need soMe training otherwise like a typical smart dalmatian he will counter surf and get into the trash in search of a tasty meal or trait. "
OTHER:
Barks at someone when they come to the door.
Very smart, already learned to open the wire gate.
Cute little crooked tail, probably a birth mishap.
Loves the confort of a nice pillow to settle down and sleep with.
House trained.
Answers to a whistle.
Needs leash and harness training for walking.

animal.description:
My name is Nedra, but Joy might be a good nickname because I am joyful all the time. I may be shy for a moment, but warm up quickly to be my affectionate and playful self. I’m known for my precious smile, and all 50 pounds of me is just one cuddly lap dog. My favorite toy is my giant Kong octagonal ball. I really like to play with other dogs once we get to know each other. I enjoy short walks and LOVE to go for car rides in my foster’s convertible. If you’re looking for close encounters of the boxer kind, please send in your adoption application and ask for joyful little ole me.

In order to qualify for ALIVE Rescue Memphis's program all of the following steps must be met:

 •You must be at least 21 years of age and be able to provide ALIVE with proof of age.

 •Any current pets must be up to date on vaccinations, and be spayed/neutered. Exceptions to this will only be considered if proof of a medical explanation is provided.

 •If you currently rent, you must provide a landlord’s phone number and a copy of your executed lease.

 •All members of the family living in the home where the animal will be placed must be interviewed.

 •Applicant must live within 50 miles of Memphis if interested in adopting and within 30 miles of Memphis if interested in fostering. 

 •Allow an ALIVE Rescue Memphis representative into your home for a visit to insure that your home is safe for the potential new pet.  

  •You must allow an ALIVE Rescue Memphis representative into your home for a visit to ensure that your home is safe for the potential new pet. 

  •You must be able and willing to spend the time and money necessary to provide training, medical treatment, and proper care for a pet.

  •Currently, adoptions fees in Memphis are $275 for a dog over 4 months of age, $300 for a dog under 4 months of age. 

  •We require an additional $75 training deposit at the time of adoption. You will be required to enroll and complete a training class with your new companion at one of our approved training facilities. Once ALIVE Rescue Memphis receives proof of the completed class, this $75 deposit will be refunded.

Hiro is a strikingly handsome, 4 year old male Japanese/American Akita. He is just 80lb, and has a

beautiful, soft, shiny blond coat.

Hiro is an easy going Akita and will enjoy hanging out with you or going for a car ride. He has zero separation anxiety so will likely take a nap if you leave. He is such a love, with the sweetest and brightest brown eyes. He would love nothing more than to be your loyal, lifelong, companion.

Want to Get One Step Closer to Adopting your New Furry Family Member?

Visit our website at www.akitaangels.org. Under the ADOPT link, download an application. Complete/scan in PDF format and return to: angels@akitaangels.org.

No Scanner? There are many FREE apps. We like "SCANNABLE."

All animals in our adoption program are spayed or neutered; are up to date with vaccinations/rabies vaccination); microchipped; and have received a well-health check by a licensed veterinarian.

Want to learn more? Email us at angels@akitaangels.org

animal.description:
UPDATE -  Wesley's has been Adopted


Meet Wesley.  He is 2 years old and is looking for his forever home.  He is a sweet, sensitive and loving boy.  He is being fostered together with one of our other young male dalmatians named Pongo.
 His Foster home reports:
"Wesley will rock your world! He is 2 years old, 50 lbs of energy with a dash of charm. His markings are striking, complete with a ½ black and ½ white tail. He loves all people and quickly bonds to humans. He is currently fostered with Pongo in San Diego, and did well meeting the other medium to large size dogs that permanently reside in his foster home.  
He loves to give his humans hugs and kisses and holds on tightly.  He is very playful and needs an active single or couple to take him on walks, runs and playtime.  Wesley is just a happy-go-lucky dog who follows the pack.    So far he has been doing very well in his foster home.   He will need positive reinforcement training once he settles in his new forever home.   He wants every bit of love and attention that you have to give. Overall, he is the sweetest, most loyal dog you could ask for. He likes to have skin to skin contact when settling in for the night and everyone is asleep.  He is a snuggle bunny and very affectionate.  
He has not been introduced to young children, cats or small dogs yet.  Showed curiosity when he saw some feral cats but did not react as strongly as his foster housemate Pongo."
OTHER:
Loves treats, loves to play.
Give him a pillow to sleep with, seems to settle him down quietly.
House trained.
Answers to a whistle.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
NORI - We got a call from a woman who said she lost her house in the fire and could we help her rehome her husky mix. Of course, we said yes. When the woman brought the dog NORI to cottage she said "oh by the way, and she is heartworm positive and both her ACL's are torn." Gulp. Yes, we had committed and didn't want her to suffer, so we would take her - how could we turn this sweet pup down. Nori is about 5 years old, 65 pounds, and a mix of half malamute, husky and "other breed."

We are treating her heartworm ongoing, and getting a surgeon lined up to do TWO ACL (anterior cruciate ligament) surgeries. If you would like to foster this sweetie post-surgery, please be in touch. You will enjoy her lovely temperament and great disposition.

If you would like to foster her as she goes through her treatments please let us know. She is one very sweet dog.

animal.description:
We do not know the details of Buddy's life prior to being rescued but can only assume, it was hard. Buddy was dumped in one of the highest kill shelters in Los Angeles. He was literally a sack of bones. The "owner" said, he didn't want to eat. When the shelter staff offered him some food, he practically inhaled it. Buddy was too traumatized to be up for public adoption, so he came to our rescue to recover before starting the journey of finding a new home. Buddy is at a great weight now. He's a very, very sensitive dog and will not eat when he's stressed, so you can imagine how stressed he was with his previous owner to become skin and bones.
Buddy does like certain men but in general he prefers women. He loves butt scratches and is a quiet guy. We are looking for a calm/adult (preferably 1 person household) with yard access. Buddy is great on walks but is content just being in the house and the yard.
Will you be that special person that shows Buddy, that loving homes without abuse exist?
Ingrid
(310) 480 6030
pcdrapps@yahoo.com
If you'd like to meet this cutie, please fill out our adoption application: http://www.pcdogrescue.org/online_application.html

animal.description:
Lenny is a 3 year old, 70 lb hunk of love and playfulness! Lenny currently lives in a home with big dogs, small dogs, senior dogs and even cats! He is the whole package with extra playfulness. Lenny is house trained but will have accidents if not kept on a routine. He is quiet in his kennel although if left in there for an extensive amount of time, he will have a small accident. He loves playing with other dogs and meeting new people. Lenny would be a great playmate for another dog or even frequent walking buddy for someone. Lenny is looking for a home that can give him a best friend and lots of love and treats.

animal.description:
We do not know the details of Buddy's life prior to being rescued but can only assume, it was hard. Buddy was dumped in one of the highest kill shelters in Los Angeles. He was literally a sack of bones. The "owner" said, he didn't want to eat. When the shelter staff offered him some food, he practically inhaled it. Buddy was too traumatized to be up for public adoption, so he came to our rescue to recover before starting the journey of finding a new home. Buddy is at a great weight now. He's a very, very sensitive dog and will not eat when he's stressed, so you can imagine how stressed he was with his previous owner to become skin and bones. 
Buddy does like certain men but in general he prefers women. He loves butt scratches and is a quiet guy. We are looking for a calm/adult (preferably 1 person household) with yard access. Buddy is great on walks but is content just being in the house and the yard. 
Will you be that special person that shows Buddy, that loving homes without abuse exist?
Ingrid
(310) 480 6030
pcdrapps@yahoo.com
If you'd like to meet this cutie, please fill out our adoption application: http://www.pcdogrescue.org/online_application.html

animal.description: Kahlo is the type of dog that could totally change your life. She has the ability to put a smile on any face and her bubbly personality will melt your heart in seconds. She is a huge fan of belly rubs and her most favorited past time is giving endless kisses. Kahlo is only 9 months old. She came to the rescue after suffering from a severe spinal cord injury that left her back end completely paralyzed. She now rocks a diaper and a cute little cart to help her get around. Some people might be taken back by her disability but not Kahlo, she strives to lead the most normal life possible; never letting anything get her down. With the right family, Kahlo will continue to beat the odds and change the world around her. The unconditional love she possesses allows her to accept every person and animal she meets. She is a true sweetheart! Kahlo is now looking for her foster-to-adopt family who owns their home in the central Florida area, where she won't be left home alone for more than a few hours at a time. Could you be that extra special family she is looking for? If so, please fill out our adoption screening form: https://mettarescuefamily.org/adoptable-dogs
