animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with the next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Hi there! My name is Felix! I came to Homeward Trails from Russell County. My previous owners had to surrender me because they could no longer care for me. I am a beautiful 2 year old boxer. I love meeting new people! I am very social and ready to befriend every human I see. 

My favorite things to do are wrestle in the yards with my friends and play with toys! I also love food. I haven't tried a food I didn't like! 

So I'm perfect, right? Right! Except I'm large. People have met me and loved me but every time they say, "Too big!" I didn't know being big was a bad thing... I've always been a big boy...

There's gotta be someone out there who likes big dogs, right? You do? Really!? I prefer and adult only home as the only pet so I can be spoiled rotten! Okay, well reach out to my people to set up a special VIP appointment during the week! I would love to meet you! And guess what? I am a part of the Go Fetch Program! My adoption fee is waived and I come with free bonus items when adopted! Do you love free things and big boy dogs? Well, come on!

Adoption Coordinator: Homeward Trails Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center

Includes spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
AVAILABLE NOW

Shasta is thought to be around 7 years old.  She is mother to Beebee.  She was brought in from Lake Dr., Trimble.  Shasta weighs around 50 pounds.  Shasta is a dog that needs some time to warm up to meeting new people.  She loves furry squeaky toys.  We have found that Shasta appears to be housebroken.

Shasta came into the shelter with a rear leg injury and some pretty yucky skin. She was covered in fleas. Her elbows are raw, and her fur is sparse over much of her body. In short, she’s looking a little tatty and used up.

Our biggest concern about Shasta is that she has a torn ACL. We have her on pain medication, but she's going to need surgery for the injury to completely heal.

Shasta does not do transitions well and will need a patient, experienced adopter with no children. Once Shasta settles in, however, she is sweet, sweet, sweet.  With other dogs, she can be selective on who she likes and who she doesn't like.  Shasta will need a quiet place to call home. Can you give this sweet senior a cozy bed and some TLC?

Because of the pandemic the shelter is currently adopting dogs to Athens Co. residents only.  

If you have other dogs and/or children at home you must bring them in for a meet and greet to see if they are compatible. 

Support the Athens County Dog Shelter by walking your dog or yourself!  It won't cost you a cent!  Download the app "Walk For a Dog" from http://wooftrax.com to your phone and select Athens County Dog Shelter and then take a walk!  It's great for you and your pooches plus it benefits the homeless dogs at the shelter.  Use the app each time you grab the leash.  You, your dog and the shelter will all benefit.

Please visit  http://www.amazon.com/gp/registry/wishlist/U0RLUOCMT7KI 
to see the wishlist of items that the Shelter is in need of.  Thank You!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
IF YOU'RE VIEWING THIS VIA A PET SEARCH SITE, WE'RE STILL ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS FOR OPIE. PLEASE visit our website BetterDaysRescue.org to read our policies as well as this dog's requirements/detailed profile.

**
Our dogs are placed in the Phoenix metro area, for proximity to our rescue (home checks, follow up visits, visit to finalize adoption) and for access to our veterinarian. Sorry, no exceptions.

**

Adoption begins with a Foster-To-Adopt period.

**

Opie's a bit of a conundrum - he looks like a small brown bear and moves like a fox. However, he has cat feet, laps water like a cat, and rubs gleefully on us just like a cat! He is the happiest and most grateful dog, and he's full of fun! Yes, he is a lap-pet even at his svelte weight. :) Vets estimate him as Cattledog but we're going to say there's something snuggly and gleeful in there, perhaps Husky.

Opie has some scars and though they're not immediately apparent, we suspect he had some scary encounters in his previous life. Now, he is the life of the party and so grateful for everything. He takes snacks so gently! Opie's dog-selective, so will be carefully matched to a new dog companion (a female friend might be best).

Opie seems especially considerate about using his dog-door to reach his outside patio. He prefers getting completely away from the living quarters to do his business!

If you believe you're a possible match for Opie, please complete an adoption application! Please include information regarding your experience with this breed, and with raising and training a puppy.

Opie is not a barker and seems very house-trained so could be a good companion for condo living. He really enjoys running zoomies off-leash, so requires a fenced yard.

We encourage you to register on our site and "Favorite" the dog(s) that interest you, so that you will be notified when bio, photos, or status are updated.

"Fenced yard" means, a backyard that is adjacent to and connected with your residence. (It does not mean a nearby fenced area/dog park.)
Gates must have padlocks and thresholds (cement or buried pavers to prevent digging.)
Yard and patio must be free of debris and have room for dogs to run and play *on a lawn and/or in a very shaded area.* Please do not invite us to your home if you have not yet landscaped your yard!
We do not place dogs in situations where there are "drained" or empty swimming pools, which are a fall hazard and contribute to the propogation of mosquitos.
Last and not least, we DO NOT adopt to students as we have found that they often do not know or anticipate where life will take them.

Discussion about a dog - including scheduling of a home check or other dialogue - cannot occur until we have received your completed adoption application. NO EXCEPTIONS. Thank you!

animal.description:
This 8-year-old, 8lb, poodle mix is named Clark because he was wearing a Superman costume in his profile pic when AJL first saw him, which is fitting to who he is a Super Dog. He’s had a rough life before AJL but he is a fighter and is as happy as a dog can be. He bounces up and down the stairs like a puppy, loves to go on short walks and enjoys car rides (he’ll even beat you to the driver seat). He is good with all the people that he meets. He needs to go potty every 4 hours so easy access to a backyard is important. He knows how to go potty on a pee pad if needed but he is fine holding it through the night. Clark has some medical conditions - he has a stage 5 heart murmur and the vet had to extract a good bit of his teeth due to plaque buildup so he only eats wet food. Regardless, he would flash his big smile like he doesn’t care at all. The vet recommends taking him back for a re-evaluation of his teeth next April and a re-check of his heart in November 2021.   

He would fit well in a family with a peaceful home and someone who can stay with him most of the day. He would not do well in an apartment or condo as he has a bit of separation anxiety and may cry when you leave. He would be great as an only dog or with another older dog but no cats. He does not like being in a crate and would much rather sleep next to you on the bed. He is ready for his forever home where he can give his unconditional love and find a family that can love him back. Pup, pup and away, Clark!

Indy is hoping someone will understand and work with him.
Indy is neutered, micro chipped, and up to date on all his shots.

animal.description:
"My charming black fur eye patch suits me perfectly. I like to imagine that it comes from a playful adventure.  For example, maybe it is a pirate’s eye patch. A pirate (or other) adventure with you sounds like fun!  Maybe I got a bruise while I was showing my love like a WWF wrestler, as I sometimes do, with my abundant affection, enthusiasm and 46 pounds of energy.  Or maybe my patch is there simply to make me look handsome and dashing (which I am!).  In any case, let’s become a team, so we can enjoy our next adventures together!

I am about three years old but puppy-like in my zest for life. I could be a good running partner. I enjoy treats and attention.  Some of the volunteers who walk me say I am smart and learn nicely for treats. My forever family will be an active & patient, dog-experienced one who can provide me with the mental & physical enrichment I need to be the best version of me.

My ideal home will be calm and quiet without many visitors, and I’ll be the only four-legged family member.  The staff feel that I'd likely do well with kid roommates ages 15 & older. 

I recently spent some time with a fabulous foster in a comfy home and here are some things she says about me: "He is a love bug who sleeps through the night and totally housebroken; we only use the crate if we are leaving for a while, short trip he will just lay on the couch. At night he sleeps with us, as he has to be near people! Loves to snuggle on the couch a lot of the time."

So, if you think I sound like the fur friend you could love forever, schedule an appointment here (ProvidenceAC.org/AdoptADog) today to meet me! I have my bags all packed – I just need my forever family to find me.

P.S. Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!"



**Some of this pet's photos have been provided by Crissy Everhart Photography (https://www.crissyeverhart.com) & sponsored by Subaru.
-------
During your appointment, you will be able to meet a selection of pets in the Kennels or Cattery that day. New pets are arriving daily!
-------

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. 

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description: My name is Bocephus (Bo) and I am about 3 years old.  I am very house trained and I know how to ring a bell on the door to let you know I need to go outside.  I am very loving and roll on my back for belly rubs and I am a happy go lucky guy.  I would do best in a home without small kids as I have been known to resource guard my bones and some toys. I had originally come from a bad neglect case of starvation - so feed me by myself and that may explain why I sometimes resource guard my busy bone.  I absolutely love toys....as where I came from I was deprived of all the fun and normal stuff a dog should experience - so I am living life now!  I can also jump VERY high and run very fast...so a fenced in yard would be great for me to run around and play in. I recently went home on foster with 2 wonderful people who saw my potential. I was able to watch my first football game and instantly became a Bills fan while cuddling on the couch with my foster parents. We enjoyed walks and I was eager to meet new people during our outings. I even enjoyed greeting the contractors that were in and out of the home. But unfortunately due to one of them having allergies they had to return me to the shelter after just a week. I ride wonderfully in a car and enjoy traveling. Please email or call the shelter if you think I would be a good fit in your home.

animal.description: This handsome boy is Silvio! He is around 6 years old and he is a purebred Doberman Pinscher. He is on the smaller size for a Doberman. Silvio is true to his breed and quickly warmed up to all the humans in his foster house. He is a sweetheart and loves to cuddle, but does not appear to be too interested in other dogs at this time. He is great with kids. He is more of a couch potato than a marathon runner and is always down for a good snuggle session. If you are interested in meeting Silvio, please submit an adoption application on our website. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Bobby, 5 year old, American bull dog. He was saved from a high kill shelter in Houston TX and spent some time with a trainer.  Bobby is a great dog. Extremely affectionate and obedient.  He is your typical bulldog that is independent and stubborn at times. But eager to please and Extremely food motivated.  He is medium to low activity level. He truly enjoys a good snuggle or long lasting chew toy to keep him satisfied.  He is non reactive to cats or dogs while out on walks leashed. He will coexist with female dogs but is selective and will become dominant.  Male dogs are a NO, at this time. An experienced handler will help him to continue his success.  He should not be placed in a first time dog owner or an under confident adopter, he will rule the environment.  He's not pushy, but stout and strong minded. Bobby would do best as the only pet in your home. To help Bobby and his family be successful his trainer will continue virtual sessions for a period of time. 

If interested in learning more or adoption please fill out an application 
https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Here's Rufus! He's a friendly fella we took into rescue from a workplace. He showed up there as a stray and the workers tried to find his owner to no avail.  He is a very sweet, gentle giant who loves to be an inside dog. He appears to be housetrained and loves, loves, loves being around people. He is crate trained and we are working on leash training. He will sit on command and listens well and is a big cuddle bug.  He has done well with other dogs his size. He's a little too interested in cats and we believe he would likely give chase.  He weighs about 70 pounds and is approximately 4 years old. He appears to be an American Bulldog mix.  He has been neutered, fully vaccinated and microchipped and is heartworm negative, so he is ready to be adopted! This big hunk deserves a family as awesome as he is! 

Rufus' adoption fee is $350.  Rufus is currently in his foster home in Sheridan, TX and will remain there until adopted.

animal.description:
Please meet Monty!  This gorgeous boy is 4 years old and 60 lbs and what we believe is a shepherd/chow ....I won’t lie - Monty is a bit of a challenge.  But MAN once you have his trust, you have your best friend for life.   Monty is now happily in a foster home where he shares with two -four legged friends, a feline and a 8 year old boy and is such a love with the entire family.  But as most chows -does not like strangers coming in the home - thinks he has to protect his people.  He will lunge and try to nip at strangers so a home where there is a lot of kids/people coming in and out of the house would not be a good fit.  He walks great on a leash, house trained, and doesn't chew.  I am looking for an experienced rescue dog owner/s, fenced yard, no young kids, other dogs in the home are great but lots of experience introducing dogs... and  A LOT of patience and love.   He truly is a good boy but needs to find his family who loves him for his quirkiness and will work with him and help him feel safe.   If you think you can be his person please email me at melissau.safehaven@gmail.com or use please cut and paste our direct link:

animal.description:
Name: Charlie Brown
Breed: Hound mix
Age: 5 years 
Good with adults!
Adoptable in the states of MA, CT and NH

WOOF WOOF WOOF!! Hound lovers, I'm sniffin' you out!!! My name is Charlie Brown, as I'm from the southern land of TN where everyone has two names! I'm quite the character and would love an active home that will take me on adventures like hikes and long walks! Have errands to run? I LOVE car rides and would be happy to be your copilot! I can be active, but I do come with an off switch and LOVE to nap! At home, I tend to bark at people and dogs outside of my home and alert the neighborhood (Isn't that what hounds do?!). I would benefit with structure and a daily routine in the home to keep things consistent! I plan to work (hard!) with a trainer in my next home to help with some basic training and my barking at things. I love to learn and I'm very food motivated with this sniffer of mine!! My ideal parents would have experience owning dogs. I'm a bit of the jealous type so I'd prefer to be the only animal in the house! And while you're at it, kids are scary and unpredictable so let's skip them too! 

So.. whatta ya say?! Long walk on the beach, dinner and nap and we'll say it's a FOREVER home?

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please fill out an application at survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions.

animal.description:
Kat was abandoned in an apple orchard, caught in a humane dog trap, removed with a catch poll and taken to the shelter. This did nothing to improve her trust in human kind. Yes, she was a hot mess. She was scared, snappy and defensive. She spent her first three weeks here slowly learning that the world is not such a bad place. Now, she is remarkable on the leash, is crate trained and does well with other dogs. Admittedly she still has a ways to go but she is so worth it. Kat will need patience, love and consistency to continue to grow into the dog she's supposed to be. Everyone who has witnessed Kat's journey has been amazed with her progress. We don't do many dogs that came in like Kat did and while they are never the easiest stories they are the ones that teach us the most.

Adoption donation $700
Call Kim at 425-888-9322
Please do not email

animal.description: Bootch is the shelter gossip! He loves to know what everyone is doing and wants everyone to know what he is doing. He gets right up in your business, seeks attention, and wants to cuddle in your lap. He will press his whole body into you for petting. When he's not seeking attention, he adores going for walks. The longer the better. He likes it even more if he has a running partner. Bootch also adores toys, playing and running the agility course. He is just a goofy guy who adores people and likes to greet everyone he meets. Bootch has been training wearing a muzzle due to some reactivity towards other dogs on walks. He does well in the car, and already knows some basic commands (sit, down, shake) but will need a basic obedience class and lots of structure to guide him in good doggie manners. He will thrive in an environment where he can receive lots of attention, love and exercise. He doesn't have much experience with other dogs and would need a slow and careful introduction. Want to have Bootch tell you everything that's going on in the shelter? Come to our Westside Shelter to say Hello to him! Bootch can't wait to say Hi to you. Weight: 67lbs Housetrained: Keeps his kennel clean in the shelter Dogs: meet and greet, would need a slow and careful introduction Cats: Unknown however most likely best without Children: Over 8 years old due to size, energy and food possession

THIS IS A COURTESY LISTING - PLEASE SEE CONTACT INFO AT THE END OF THE BIO

Sweet Marley was in one home all of his life. Then things changed at home and Marley was no longer wanted. He's the perfect size at about 40 lbs. Marley can be apprehensive with new people but very affectionate once he's comfortable. Marley is generally a very quiet dog but when he gets excited when you come home, he will talk a little. Very cute. Marley loves soft blankets and dog beds and rides well in the car. He's great on walks and makes sure, he doesn't leave any flower out, to be smelled. He's a bright guy who would love to spend the rest of his life in a home and not in a boarding facility. Marley is also available for long-term fostering which means, the rescue will cover any medical expenses for him. He's looking for an adult household with yard access.
Don't wait, contact us to meet Marley!
Ingrid

BALOO IS AVAILABLE BY APPOINTMENT WITH OUR ANIMAL BEHAVIOR DEPARTMENT. Please call 402.441.4490 to schedule an appointment. 


10/22/20: Baloo is such a happy boy. He is a big goofball that always has a smile on his face and his tail wagging. Baloo is a large dog that sometimes does not know his own size and could easily knock down a kid. He can also be a little mouthy when he meets people so we ask that he meets all kids prior to adoption. Baloo has a ton of energy that will need to be worn out every day. He loves to race around the backyard and will need some training to walk nicely on the leash. Baloo loves to show off his tricks that he knows and works hard for food. When meeting another dog his size, Baloo was friendly but very energetic. We ask that he meets all dogs prior to adoption and recommend he goes to a home without small dogs. Baloo was surrendered to the shelter because he had too much energy. He would do best in a home that can provide daily exercise.

animal.description:
"Hi! My name is Nico, I am around 2 years old, about 43lbs, already neutered, microchipped & up to date on vaccinations and all set to move right into your home and heart!
 
My friends here call me the cutest little chicken nugget and baby hippo. I do love chicken nuggets, and, like the hippo, I am very shy, loving and loyal to my people and fellow hippos. I would love an adult-only, kitty-free, calm, quiet home with another dog to help me build confidence. I take a little time to warm up to new people, but my friends say that once I warm up, I will give you my heart, endless laughs, kisses & cuddles. I love to play with my adult human friends, I love toys, chasing tennis balls and spending time cuddling in the warm sun. 
 
My friends here at PAC say I am a big goofball and I make them smile. I do love making them smile. I love that they are so patient with me and let me choose when I am ready to cuddle up or try new things. If you give me a chance, I would love to cuddle up with you too.  
 
If you want to meet me, please complete an adoption profile (located here: https://providenceac.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Adoption-Profile.pdf) and email it to my friend Stevie at srementer@providenceac.org and then we'll be in touch. I can't wait to meet you! XO - Nico"

P.S. Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!

**Some of this pet's photos have been provided by Crissy Everhart Photography (https://www.crissyeverhart.com) & sponsored by Subaru.
___

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description:
Big and beautiful, Cora is a large mixed breed dog weighing in at 73 pounds. Cora is strong on a leash and needs an adopter that is physically able to handle her. Overall, she appears to be human and dog friendly, but due to her strength and playfulness, we would not recommend a home with toddlers. Cora will need a family to give her daily exercise and work on her obedience and manners. In some instances, Cora can be a bit timid in some circumstances but give her a little patience and gentle positive reinforcement, she does very well.

UPDATE: Cora, although 5 years old, acts like a puppy and I suspect she has never had a lot of guidance or obedience training. She can be quiet "mouthy" and will try to jump on you - but she does listen when told "no". For these reasons, she is hard to walk on a leash, but once she calms down she will walk well. She does not seem to understand what a ball is or why you are throwing it, but does enjoy playing with ropes and is treat motivated. Cora is also very loving and will lean her whole body into you for a hug. Cora needs an adopter who will be committed to her obedience training.

animal.description: Meet Scooter! Scooter is 8 years old, neutered, and up to date on vaccinations. Scooter would make a great companion in a quiet, childless home. We don't have much of a background on his home life before the shelter, but he is a very independent dog who doesn't mind getting some attention, but otherwise is very content to be by himself. If you are sitting in the backyard with him, he likes to come over and sit at your feet and get loves and scratches. Scooter walks well on a leash and loves to go for rides in the car! When outside, Scooter needs supervision as he can easily scale a 6 foot tall fence or will dig underneath of it. Scooter would love to go home with you and lay with you all day! Scooter is Lyme positive and our vet has deemed him nonclinical, which means he has shown no symptoms. Lyme positive dogs can lead happy, healthy lives with no issue. If you had more questions on Lyme, ask your vet for more information if you were interested in adopting a Lyme positive dog!  If you would like more information on Scooter, please give us a call at (540) 778-2101 to ask for an application!

animal.description:
Meet Honey! Honey is a one year old girl who was surrendered to us when she didn't live up to the adopters expectations. (Right?) Honey is a petite little girl, about 43lbs. She's high energy and a snuggler all rolled into one tiny package! She LOVES kids!! But she HATES cats. Honey would do best in either a only dog home or with a dog who matches well with her after the alloted shutdown decompression time. It takes her a minute to warm up to them. She currently lives with a small dog who doesn't care for her and a large Husky - who she gets along great with. Honey will follow your kids around ALL DAY LONG  then snuggle up to take a nap. She needs to work on her leash manners though - she gets SUPER excited and can sound intimidating (like a Hyena) When she's not screaming like a Hyena with excitement, she snorts like a little pig when she's playing with the kids. Honey is crate trained, and has zero accidents in the foster home. Due to her still having lots of puppy energy, a home with a fenced yard is best. She can be walked daily as well, but will need an owner who will devote some time to leash training as she was never walked much prior to coming to rescue. If you are looking for a pretty little pitty, Honey is your girl. 

To schedule a home visit and meet and greet, please fill out our adoption application. https://queencitypitties.com/adoption-application/


We cannot accept applications from Canada or far distances from Buffalo.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Honey does not do well with cats or any small rodent, like rabbits.

animal.description:
MEET ROCKY-Little dog, BIG personality! Rocky prefers to be your devoted one and only and is looking for a quiet home without other pets or children in a quiet neighborhood.

Rocky is looking for his fairy tale ending. Our story begins with our hero down on his luck, found as a stray, heartworm positive, and desperate for a safe place to lay his head. When all hope seemed lost, animal control swooped in to save him.  Puppy Paws Rescue was contacted, and this is where Rocky’s story turned to one of hope. Nervous, confused, and unable to believe this dream could be his new reality, Rocky slowly learned to trust his foster family. Rocky has been treated for heartworms, neutered, microchipped, house and crate trained. There is only one final step-to find his happily ever after.

Rocky is a 3-4 years old, 10 lbs Chihuahua mix. He is spunky has a true ZEST for life! He loves to prance around the neighborhood on his walks and explore all the sights and sounds. Rocky is completely devoted to his people; he is very loving and playful with the children and other family members in his foster home. Due to his size, Rocky will need a home with no children as he can easily get under foot and can be nippy when excited. He can also be growly if he is scared. Rocky loves to be curled up in a lap or snuggled up on the dog bed under his foster mom's desk while she works. For that reason, he is looking for a home where someone is home more often than not. 

Rocky can be very shy/nervous meeting new people and will need time to warm up in new situations. Any potential adopter will need to understand that the shy/nervous dog they meet initially will transform into one that is happy and playful- once settled-he will be all smiles as he playfully  darts around the house.

Overall, Rocky is fine with the big dogs in his foster home, he loves to play with them and curl up with them. However, just like any typical chihuahua, he is jealous and protective of his person's lap. He will growl and snap if other dogs come to get attention when he is with his person. Rocky's ideal home would be where he has all the love and attention as an only dog. Rocky cannot be in a home with dogs larger than him who may not tolerate his confident attitude as he could be injured. He has not been cat tested.

Rocky is an active little guy that will need daily exercise, but he also loves to hang out on the couch. He loves his chew toys and his stuffed animals-and is very good at entertaining himself with those toys. He finds sheer joy in each and every moment. All he wants is your love and attention- in return he will be your absolute best and most loyal friend-always sure to bring a smile to your face with his silly antics and devotion.

Rocky has recently finished his crate rest period after being treated for heartworms. After heartworm treatment and crate rest, dogs can be expected to test positive for up to 6 months.

If interested in adopting please fill out our no obligation online application at www.puppypawsrescue.org

Note: Our rescue requires that all adopter's current and prior animals are up-to-date on vaccinations (DHLPP & Rabies) and preventatives (heartworm and flea and tick), unless there is a medical reason not allowing it. All animals in your household should be spayed or neutered unless medically indicated that they should not be or are currently still too young.

animal.description:
TO CONTACT THE FOSTER HOME, email mrulffes@gmail.com. DO NOT use the Petfinder form. Inquiries don't reach us.

Hi!  My name is Pinn (short for Pinnacle as mama says I am destined to rise high to the top).  I am a 38 pound, 9 year old blue girl who is very very shy.  I really don’t like to talk about myself, but mama says you need to know a little bit about me to fall in love with me.  Please don’t ask me to tell you where I came from or all I have been through as it makes my heart hurt and makes mama cry.  Mama says no looking back, we are only looking forward to all the things I am going to accomplish in the rest of my years!!
As you can see, I am truly a beautiful girl.  Mama says I have very good manners and am very well behaved.  I walk nicely on a leash, but when out playing in the yard with my friend Abbie, I always come when mama calls me.  I am completely house trained, no accidents for this girl; and I am crate trained.  My favorite thing in the whole world is belly rubs, lots and lots of belly rubs and I know how to use my nose to push your hand and arm to the right spot on my belly.  I am starting to like kisses and occasionally I will give mama a kiss right on her nose.  I like pillows and blankets when I am on the couch and have learned how to arrange them just right so I am comfy.  My foster mom and dad are crazzzzzzzzy and have ten other dogs in the house right now that I do pretty well with.  I have just one I am not particularly fond of, but mama says nobody is particularly fond of her.  But………………….I honestly would prefer to be your one and only as I like a nice calm space and want to make sure you have plenty of time to rub my belly, just my belly!

Now mama says we have to not only share the good, but we also have to share things to work on.  My start in life wasn’t ideal so I need a quiet, calm home that will be very patient and understanding that I need some time to make sure I can trust you.  I trust the ladies much quicker than the guys!  Foster dad has been very patient with me and lets me take the lead in our relationship.  The good news is after several weeks I let foster mom pet me, snuggle me and oh does she ever give the best belly rubs.  Recently I have even let her wrap her arms around me for a real hug.  Small humans make me very nervous so mama says no homes with small ankle biters.  I like nice quiet spaces so mama says city life is not for me and apartment/townhouse living where I might have to meet lots of new people will make me very anxious so a nice country setting would be my happy place.  Oh and I love to go on car rides with mama, and I ride every so nicely.  So if you would like to take a chance on an old lady, foster mama says fill out an application and she will be in touch!!
 
Foster mom here:  Our Pinn is a very special girl who will need a calm, quiet, patient home, who will be willing to give her several weeks to warm up to any new person.  She does not have one ounce of aggression in her body, she distances herself in the beginning until she is ready for you to come into her comfort zone.  If she is uncomfortable she removes herself from the situation until she is ready to try again.  She is very fearful of new men, tolerates my husband and will occasionally give him a nose bump while he is sitting in his office.  Kids make her very very nervous; she removes herself from the room when they are too close.  She has become my Velcro girl as she follows me everywhere and keeps me in her sight at all time and I am confident she will do the same with her new people.  She loves a good car ride!  
 
Pinn is being fostered in Canton, NY.  If you would like more information about Pinn or have any questions you can email her foster mom at mrulffes@gmail.com  If you would like to submit an application for Pinn, please visit our website at acdra.org.

COMPLETE AN APPLICATION
http://www.acdra.org/adoption-application

*****************************************************************
--ABOUT NACHO--
Nacho is a Diamond in the Ruff! Interested adopters should visit his page at www.buddydoghs.org/nacho to view his story, adopter requirements, and more photos and videos!

Key Notes:
-6 year old neutered male.
-Chihuahua mix.
-24 pounds and overweight.
-Surrendered by extended family to a rescue in Alabama when his elderly owner passed.
-Experience with reactive or aggressive dogs needed.
-Adopter must own their home. No apartments, multi-family homes, or cities.
-Needs an adult-only (18+) home.
-Should be an only pet, with the exception of his friend, Candy. May be able to eventually live with another dog with training.
-Territorial of his space; needs little to no visitors and a separate and secure space for when there are visitors.
-No more than 8 hours alone a day.
-Low-medium energy; loves walks and the occasional run, but happy to laze around.
-Ideally just 1-2 adults for him to bond with.
-Very housebroken and good on leash.
-Behavioral training recommended.
-Overweight; needs help losing weight with diet and exercise. He's already successfully lost 12 pounds!
-Nacho is typically his most well behaved on walks and for treats. These will both help bond with him and help him lose weight.

--THE ADOPTION PROCESS--
If you are interested in adopting this animal, please submit an online application. Applications will be reviewed as received. If in our opinion a pet is a good candidate for you, an adoption counselor will contact you to schedule a zoom chat. If you do not hear from us it simply means either the animal has been adopted or we have not received the right pet for you. The application process is at no charge to you and only needs to be completed once as all applications will be kept on file.

Online applications can be found here: www.buddydoghs.com/forms

Check out our FAQ for answers to most questions here: www.buddydoghs.com/faq

Adopters must be at least 21 years of age and a Massachusetts resident.

Meet Wednesday! This sweet girl has been through a lot! When she came to the Shelter, she had been treated for bite wounds..poor thing! Since then, Wednesday has been diagnosed with Heartworm Disease...double poor thing! Despite all this, Wednesday is a lovely girl, who enjoys being with people and her fellow canines! She deserves, very much, to be in a loving, safe and secure home. Wednesday will thrive in a home with adult children, who can be helpful with her ongoing care! Don't miss the chance to meet this incredibly wonderful girl.

The following descriptions describe behaviors that were observed during testing and/or veterinary examination: Evaluated for temperament with 335035 (male) and 334858 (female). Did well with both. She does vocalize when the other dogs are removed from the room. 10/29/2020

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.

Wednesday has heart worm disease, and is currently in treatment. She will be on restricted activity (SHORT LEASH WALKS ONLY, NO FREE RUNNING!) until her treatment is completed. She will require regular visits to a veterinarian, and a monthly heart worm preventative for the rest of her life.

READ THE FOLLOWING FOR INSTRUCTIONS ON SUBMITTING AN APPLICATION AND FOR A DESCRIPTION  OF THIS PET:

Millie is your ideal shadow dog - in the mood for a rainy-day snuggle sesh all day?  She's your girl.  Fixing for a game of catch in the backyard or a nice brisk walk? So is she! Millie is as active (or inactive) as you want her to be, making her an ideal household pet! She loves to have the full attention of her humans, so her best home would be one with no other dogs, and older kids would be best. 
She adores people and everyone who shows her affection!  

Millie is approximately 8 years old and weighs about 50lbs.  Millie is fully vetted including all vaccines, spayed, microchipped, and has had a dental.  Millie also had surgery to remove polyps from her ears due to years of neglect, but it does not seem to have affected her hearing.

Millie's adoption fee is $275, please consider this sweet senior!

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING, PLEASE READ THE FOLLOWING INSTRUCTIONS:

- The first step towards adoption is to complete an adoption application, which can be found online at our website www.roadtriprescues.com, under the “ADOPT” tab.

- Do not use the Petfinder links or email to ask us about our adoptable dog listings - we do not always receive these messages and will not respond to them.

- Please do not ask if a dog is still available - we do our best to update their status as quickly as possible.  If a dog is listed for adoption, it means we have not yet approved an adopter and are still accepting applications.

- PLEASE NOTE THAT ONLY APPROVED ADOPTERS WILL BE PERMITTED TO MEET OUR RESCUES - WE ARE A FOSTER BASED RESCUE AND ALL OF OUR DOGS LIVE WITH US AS FAMILY. 

Thanks for considering a rescue pup!

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Sherman and my foster mom says I am super handsome and have the potential to make you Instagram famous with my goofy toothless smile and tiny little brindle ears. I am about 8 years old and discovered 4 months ago that there are so many things I've missed out in life so I'm ready to try out anything you introduce to me. So far, I've discovered belly rubs, nice comfy beds, and a clean bath and I love them all.  I will even let you wash me every other day if you really want to. In fact, my foster mom tried to "torture" me by washing me every other day so I just hang out in the bathtub and wait for my next bath! I also absolutely love any treats but prefer big bones to chew on. Cats and small dogs are great friends because we all just mind our own business. Big dogs are great as well but it just takes me about 2 weeks to get used to them. Once I know them well, I prefer to do whatever they do! I am heartworm positive so I prefer short walks throughout the day because I get tired after about 15 minutes of walking on the leash. I haven't been trained until recently so I don't really know any tricks and cannot fetch but I have a great attitude and will smile at you all day if you teach me positively. I've been telling Santa that I've been a good boy and would like to be “hired” to love my own humans. Are you ready to hire/adopt me?


Important notes: Sherman needs to be introduced to dogs slowly but should fit in just fine. However, he's great with cats from the start.

animal.description:
Bear is a 1-2 year old Shar-Pei mix. He is soooo darned handsome! He is a bit tentative until he gets to know you. Patience will be key when working with him. A couple of visits may be required until he has warmed up to you. We have a volunteer program at the rescue called our "best buddy" program. A volunteer will choose a specific dog to spend time with on a weekly basis. It help the dogs to learn to develop trust, and builds relationships between the dogs and humans. Bears' "best buddy" takes him for car rides and ice cream on a regular basis and they truly are the best of friends. His tentative nature is replaced with joy when he sees his best buddy. All it will take is patience and a bit of time and Bear could be a loyal, loving companion. We would suggest no small children. Older kids who understand boundaries would most likely be ok. He did get along with the dogs in his previous home since he was raised with them, but there would be a meet and greet required with any other resident dogs. A physical fence would be required.

AHeinz57 Pet Rescue and Transport is a 501c3 no-kill animal rescue located in De Soto, Iowa. Our pets are located at our facility and in foster homes around Central Iowa. We do adopt to out of town applicants, however we do require new family members be picked up in person. 

If you are interested in meeting one of our adorable adoptables, the first step in our process is to complete an adoption application. To complete an application or read more about our adoption process, please visit our website:

https://www.aheinz57.com/adopt-a-pet/adoption-process/
Our adoption fees are:

$300 - Puppies (up to 6 months)

$195 - Dogs age 6 months - 7 years

$100 - Senior Dogs (age 8 and up)

$200 - Bonded Buddies

$100 - Kittens (up to age 6 months)

$150 - 2 Kittens

$60 - Cats age 6 months and up

$90 - 2 Cats

For the most up-to-date listing of adoptable animals, please visit our website: https://www.aheinz57.com/adopt-a-pet/

Thank you for considering adopting a rescue animal!

Her coat is a little rough and her ears, when straight up, remind us of a shepherd.  Taren is a large dog, weighing 70 pounds and could stand to lose a few pounds (don’t tell her we said that!)  

Taren was pulled from our local animal shelter where she had been picked up as a stray and no one came to claim her.  Taren is very sweet, loving and social.  She is pretty laid back but does like to talk to you if she is not getting attention!  

Taren has nice energy and will require a fenced in backyard to run and play in.  But she is NOT to be an outside dog only cause she loves to be with her pack.  She is too big for an apartment.  

She seems to get along with other dogs and should be fine with older children, just not young children she might could easily knock over by accident.  We have started on her crate training.  Taren is up to date on her vet care, spayed, heartworm negative and is microchipped.  She is on heartworm and flea/tick preventions.  What a great dog to snuggle up with on a cold night!!

Our Adoption Questionnaire is at http://www.scgsr.org/aq/

About Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue

Second Chance German Shepherd Rescue is a non-profit, volunteer-run, foster-based German Shepherd Dog rescue serving the greater Bay Area and Sacramento/Roseville regions of Northern California. 

Our primary focus is rescuing German Shepherd Dogs from life threatening situations in overcrowded shelters where they are in danger of being put to sleep. We adopt our dogs into loving, responsible permanent homes. German Shepherd Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, and receive basic veterinary care while they await placement in their permanent homes. We work with area shelters and other rescue groups to develop a network of support for German Shepherd Dogs in need.

SCGSR Adoption Process

We get most of our dogs from the shelters where their previous owners did not provide much training or socialization so they tend to need some training and/or management in order to successfully integrate them into a new household. We have an adoption process to help decide which type of home would be good for the typical dog we get into our rescue. 

Our adoption process is:
Fill out and submit an adoption questionnaire. Have a phone interview. Have an in person home visit - this requires you to be located in one of the following areas where our volunteers live so they can do the required in person home visit: East Bay, South Bay, Peninsula, San Francisco and Marin areas, and in and around the Fresno, Sacramento and Roseville areas. We do not adopt outside of our volunteer area for the safety of our dogs as we need to be able to remove them from a home if things are not working out well e.g. with existing pets.

Adopters who already have had an approved home visit have priority to adopt available dogs. Our adoption fees are $350 for dogs under one year, $300 for dogs one year to six years, and $250 for dogs older than six years. If you do not own your own home your landlord must sign our landlord approval form.  Email us at info@scgsr.org to get our landlord approval form.

Thank you for considering a rescue German Shepherd Dog.

Our super sweet little blue pittie princess came to us from death row in NC.  

She is about 3 years old, and the sweetest soul with mild energy.  She loves snuggles and makes adorable snorting noises when you scratch the right spot.  She will also politely ask for more scratches if she hasn’t had enough.  She plays well with other dogs but wants a home where she can be the only princess.

She is sponsored by Kennel To Couch, meaning she has prepaid training sessions with SitMeansSit of Baltimore.  Additionally, she has already had a professional training evaluation where she got great reviews!

She is in the end of treatment for heartworms.  She has received injections and in 4 weeks will officially be considered heartworm free!  We can answer any questions you have about the process and are delighted to support you through it!  All costs are covered by the rescue.

To apply please visit theherorescue.com/available-for-adoption .

Meet Landry! Landry is a 2-year-old Shepherd/Lab mix. D.O.B. 10/29/18. Landry has had a rough start to life and was found very underweight and living in a hoarding situation with many other dogs. Due to her past situation and having very little human interaction, Landry is fearful of new people and can be quite skittish. She will need someone who is willing to come meet her several times and spend some time getting to know her before she is comfortable with you and trusts you. Once Landry warms up to you, she's a big lovebug who just wants to follow you around and get lots of belly rubs. Time, patience, and lots of treats will help win this sweet girl over. She currently weighs 51 lbs. She has been dewormed, is UTD on shots. She came to us heartworm positive and received heartworm treatment early January. Our minimum adoption age is 23 and our dog adoption fee is $275. Call us at 843-427-4388 to make an appointment to meet our adoptable dogs!

Dog adoption fee is $275 and includes spay/neutering and immunizations required based on age prior to adoption. Fees also include other medical and physical care provided while at the shelter.

animal.description:
Meet Betsy! 
This sweet girl wants nothing more than to be with her person(s). Betsy is one of those special dogs that will truly be your best friend and loving companion. She is a 5 year old, 55 lb, Black Mouth Cur/Bullmastiff/Boxer mix. Betsy can be a bit shy when first meeting you but quickly warms up with some gentle pets or a treat. She loves walks and does great on leash. Betsy is playful and loves to run and do zoomies around the backyard. After playtime she will be snuggling up next to you on the sofa. Betsy can be iffy with other dogs so she would prefer to be the only dog in the home. Betsy is a loving dog and a wonderful,  companion but she is definitely a dog that attaches to her person(s)  and can be protective of them. She would do best in an adult only home without alot of visitors coming in and out and one that is able to provide a safe and separate area that she can go to when company does come for a visit.  Betsy is house and crate trained, fully vetted, UTD on all vaccines and preventatives, HW tested, spayed and microchipped.  
if you are interested in meeting Betsy please email us at huntershoperescue@gmail.com for an application. 

Questions? Please email is
us at huntershoperescue@gmail.com. 
We are all volunteers with jobs and families in addition to our rescue dogs. We do our best to respond within 24 hours but please be patient. Applicants under 25 years of age will need to demonstrate an adult lifestyle. If you rent your home we require a letter from the landlord submitted with your application granting permission for a pet.  A fenced yard is preferred.

animal.description:
"Hey there! Have you ever seen a dog as adorable as me?! Can you believe I’m homeless and am waiting for a wonderful person or family to adopt me? Great dogs like me end up in animal shelters every day- I know, it’s so hard to believe but it’s true!

My name is Bonnie, and I just joined the adoptable doggy crew at Providence Animal Center. I traveled to PA all the way from Georgia after I was brought in as a stray. I'm around 1 year old, about 43 pounds, and I'm all set to move right into your heart & home today - already spayed, microchipped & up to date on vaccinations. 

The staff think my ideal home would be a quiet home without a lot of visitors or dogs. I'm a sweet girl but I get nervous meeting new people. It takes me some time to get comfortable with new people, but once you gain my trust I'm just a wiggly, happy love bug. I will offer lots of hugs and kisses.  I also take treats gently and I already know "sit" and "down". I have a love for the outdoors -- often  getting super pumped to go on hikes and walks. What can I say, nature soothes my soul. Bonus (not a must) in my forever home would be a fenced yard, as I love running around in free space! 

I have responded well to marker/clicker training and if you don't know what that is here's a link to a video explaining what it is: https://youtu.be/_wv1uvvqaSw, Oh, the staff also think I may be able to have a feline roommate with a proper introduction AND if you have children, they think I would do best with children that are 15 years old or older. 

So who's into learning how to clicker train with me? I'm promise I will be worth the time and effort! The staff would love to match you with your new best friend forever - and hopefully that's me! If you are interested in meeting me in person, please email your completed adoption profile (located here: https://providenceac.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Adoption-Profile.pdf) to my pal Stevie at srementer@providenceac.org. My paws are crossed I will see you very soon! 

XOXO Bonnie

P.S. Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!"

-------

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description: I weigh approximately 48 lbs. Are you ready to get down and boogie? Then we have just the pup for you! It's... wait for it, wait for it... Boogie! His shelter friends have described him as sweet, ridiculous, firecracker, hilarious. So basically, the total package! Boogie loves to meet new people but he can be a bit... um, enthusiastic with his greetings. What we mean is, he may accidentally headbutt you while trying to give you a kiss. Ruh roh! Boogie is working on reigning it in, but it's hard y'all! All that energy and living in a shelter kennel most of the day... it's tough on this young, smart pup. Boogie is also an athletic dude... zoomies, fetching, and toy-tossing are his current top 3 sports. We have no doubt he would excel in agility if given the opportunity! Boogie went on a hike recently and omigosh... all the smells! All the sights! All the everything! He declared it was the Best Day Ever. Boogie got an A on his report card after a recent outing with our trainer. He loved riding in the car... just looking out the window and taking it all in. At the house, he was excited initially and then settled in and entertained himself with various toys. The trainer said Boogie is a super smartpants with plenty of energy and a soft heart. We agree! Boogie would do best with an active adopter who takes him on walks (or runs!) and also works his brain with puzzle toys and focus games. We think he'd do great with teenagers but he's too much doggo for little kids. Boogie may be able to live with another dog in the future but he needs to go to a pet-free home for now. Boogie needs someone willing to give him time to decompress and help him find his groove. Boogie will go home with tons of support from the Orange Dot Crew (a volunteer advocacy group at the shelter), a goody bag of enrichment items, and free training support thanks to Friends of AAC and their Behavior Assistance Program!

animal.description:
Little Tyson (formerly known as Maloney) found himself at risk of euthanasia at a NYC shelter where he arrived as a stray. Now, Tyson is with a foster family that can no longer keep him due to their own personal/medical issues.

He is a 4 year old, 40 lb. boxer mix that is a sweet (but stubborn) medium-energy level pup. He does have some health issues and some behavior issues, but nothing major that can’t be overcome as he has so much to offer the right family! 

Here’s what Tyson has to say:

“I am a funny little guy - apparently I do things to make my foster moms laugh everyday. I love being near my humans and I will cry if I don’t know where they are because I’m so afraid of being abandoned again. My favorite things to do are curling up and hanging out with you, eating, and sunbathing! 

I am not sure what happened to me when I was on the streets of the city, but I must've learned I had to protect myself so sometimes I can be reactive when I’m surprised or scared - especially if you startle me out of a sound sleep, or if you come into a dark room and I can’t see you….it takes me a minute to realize you aren’t going to hurt me. I’m told I can also be super stubborn at times, but my Kryptonite (my favorite treats that I can't resist) is fresh vegetables, believe it or not - carrots and tomatoes especially! My foster moms have gotten me on a very healthy diet.

I also really love having a fur-sibling to run, play, and wrestle with. My foster moms also think a fur-sibling is important because it helps remind me how well-adjusted dogs behave due to my underdeveloped social skills early on in my life. But - I don’t necessarily love *all* other doggies - I’m selective and will need to decide for myself if we can be bff’s.

I do have a health issue (kidney disease) but that just means special food that the vet orders for me and having the vet check my kidney levels twice a year. I need to drink lots of water, too, and be able to go potty every few hours. This condition probably happened to me when I was on the streets of NYC and did not have a family to care for me. I also have a seasonal skin allergy (seasonal alopecia). It is not a big deal, and I’m told it’s common in Boxers; just a special shampoo and some sunbathing time to keep my skin and fur nice. 

I walk really well on my leash, am housebroken, and I know my basic commands. I’m also very intelligent! I’ve even learned that when my fur-brother runs zoomies through the house, instead of chasing him, I’ll just wait for him to come back around to start wrestling again! :-D

I really want a forever home but I’m afraid I won’t find one….do you think you can help me?”

Tyson's current foster moms have done a fantastic job with Tyson’s health and diet, his leash skills, and basic training — now he needs someone to take him to the next level. “Underneath his challenges, Ty really is a wonderful dog!” say his foster moms. “He’s such a goof ball (just don’t tell him that!), and his face could melt a thousand hearts. He deserves to be with a family who is ready and able to invest the time and effort into helping him be the best pup he can be. To help keep his moods even, medication might be an option worth exploring."
 
------------------------------

Tyson will do best in a home with:

- A fursibling that he can play with! (exuberant/playful medium sized dog/s)
- An experienced, adult-only home where someone is home all or most of the time
- Low to moderate-energy activity level home
- Committed to his special needs (kidney diet dog food, fresh vegetables, seasonal medicated baths)

------------------------------

Tyson is neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped. To learn more, please contact AmsterDog at info@amsterdog.org or fill out our application at www.amsterdog.org/application to get the process started.

Thank you for caring about a pet in need!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Faith. I can't sing, but I do have many nicknames, wigglebutt being the number 1. When you see me, you'll know why. I get so excited when people give me attention that I wag my tail so hard, that my whole butt shakes. You can see it in the video attached to my bio. 

My foster parents brag about me all the time. Everyone can see how cute I am and feel how soft I am, but once you get to know me you'll see what a good girl I am. I am just the perfect size for a pet (about 40lbs) All I want is to be loved and snuggled. My foster parents finally figured out that when I say ""love"" I mean everything that goes with it like boundaries, a routine and a safe environment like my crate at night. I sleep really well in there. 

Don't get me wrong, I love to be spoiled, but I am a very smart dog and respond well to structure. I am a little over 2 so I am a pretty good house dog too! I know lots of basic commands, I don't get into anything I shouldn't, I am well potty trained and I don't even beg. I go lay on my dog bed with my sad puppy eyes like a good girl when my humans eat...if they tell me to. I love to play catch outside, play with my Kong and stuffed squeakers. But my favorite thing is to rollover and have you rub my belly. I'm really enjoying my current foster home that has no pets. I have been known to play well with other dogs, but have been having trouble settling in to Minnesota. I think I might need a little time on other pets for now. 

Other than that, I really want to make my forever home with you as soon as you see me. I know you want it too. Set up a time to meet me, you won't be disappointed. 



FOSTER TO ADOPT:
Faith Hill just completed Heartworm treatment and is waiting for a negative test result which can take 2-9 months after treatment. During these months, she will need to make sure her heart rate is not elevated due to high energy play or exercise. Faith Hill is only available through the Foster to Adopt Program at this time. The commitment will be for an adoption but will be fostering until she is cleared with a negative Heartworm test result. All of the medical expenses will be paid for by the rescue while she is in a foster to adopt home. Food, kennel, grooming and other supplies will be provided by the foster in the foster to adopt program. 


For a video of Faith please visit: 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cEpfVJlbopI&feature=youtu.be


--------------------------------------------


All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Adoption Fee - $450

To apply for this pup, please submit an Adoption Application at http://warriordogrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

PLEASE READ: The clinics are not open for viewing animals. If you are interested in meeting this pet, please email information about yourself, family, residence and current/prior pet experience. If it is a good fit you will be sent an application. Once that is approved, arrangements will be made for a meeting. Thanks for your understanding!

Meet Casper! Casper was brought to us when his time was up at a Kentucky animal control. Casper was brought in as a stray and never reclaimed after another dog attacked him while he was running the streets. His leg injury was so severe that he needed a leg amputation upon arrival. Casper is a very good boy and very friendly with people.  He seems to do well with most other dogs, but has been stand offish with some. This isn't surprising due to his history of being attacked. We believe he would do well with a vast majority of dogs. We are unsure if Casper is good with cats. Casper's adoption fee is $259, which includes his medical since arriving, neuter, microchip, vaccinations and routine labwork. If interested in adopting, please email us about your household so we can begin the application process. Once approved, we can move forward with scheduling a meet and greet/adoption appointment.


Email inquires can be directed to availablepets@gmail.com.
Adoption donations for adult dogs range from $59 to $299 and puppies from $159 to $599. This includes: 
-  Spay or neuter surgery
Vaccines current to the date of adoption*: 
  -  Rabies vaccine
  -  Bordatella vaccine
  -  Booster for canine Distemper, Adenovirus type 1 & 2, Leptospirosis,
      Parainfluenza, Parvovirus, and Coronavirus (DHLPPC)
  - Canine Influenza vaccine
-  Fecal test
-  1st worming 
-  Heartworm test (+6 months old) 
-  Capstar flea treatment
-  Microchip identification implant
* Boosters required for puppies and kittens (depending on age) POST adoption are the responsibility of the pet owner.
 
Heartworm prevention must also be purchased at the time of adoption and prices vary depending on the size of the animal being adopted.  Puppies under 6 months old are required to sign up for a puppy obedience class. ($89 deposit required, refundable upon completion)

Come Ready to Adopt: 
If you rent or live in a condo/townhouse with an association, bring your lease/bylaws indicating pets are allowed and if there are any restrictions. We require vaccinations and tests to be up to date for the protection of your current pets. Bringing their vet records can help speed the adoption process. All adults in the household must be present and co-sign the application.

animal.description:
Thank you for considering a homeless/rescue dog, it does not matter where dogs are from what matters is where they will live the rest of their life. 

Gracie is a precious Plott Hound mix her face is all hound with big floppy ears all sweetness from her head to the tip of her tail.  She is 55 pounds of sweetness, her age is difficult to identify without proper knowledge of ancestry; a guess assessment of breed and age has been made at 2 – 2 ½ years old.  

Gracie was once a stray undernourished, homeless and neglected looking for her next meal.  She had an unhappy beginning no one to hold her with loving hands, no socialization she deserves a second chance at happiness.  She was extremely shy and timid but much progress has been made Gracie is in foster care in a loving home with a very understanding, patient loving foster mom.   As shown in her video she allows her foster mom to pet her, feed her snacks and she comes to her when called, Gracie has gained her trust which did not happen overnight.   She is also friendly with her feline friends she enjoys playing with them.

When Gracie was rescued she was extremely skittish around new people/strangers her foster mom is working diligently showing Gracie that not all people are bad.  Gracie will enjoy a home with a resident pooch to play with and learn confidence from her friend.   

Gracie will need a patient family who will allow her to open up on her own time.  Gracie will learn through another dog friend and she would be her happiest with a confident, independent dog in the home learning to mimic the positive behaviors of the confident dogs around her. Time, space, and a confident dog friend and family will be the key to allow Gracie to be her true happy self. It won't happen overnight, but with patience Gracie will definitely come around and look to you for affirmation.

Gracie is smart, silly and playful she loves her toys and enjoys running in a secure fenced yard which will be necessary for her to experience freedom in the safety of her own yard. a fenced yard is preferred which will be necessary for her.  Gracie has a sweet and playful personality; she will be a good companion and a friend for life.  She loves the outdoors; smelling all the great outdoors whiffs.  She enjoys her one-on-one time and being scratched and a serious belly rub she will always welcome, last but not least a good tasty treat.  

On first encounters sudden, fast, jerky movements and loud sounds may intimidate Gracie.  She’s looking for a nice quiet home to hang her leash and call “Home sweet home”.  Please be that special person Gracie needs.   Timid shy stray rescue dogs have not been adequately socialized with people so it can take longer for them to warm up to people with whom they are unfamiliar. It could take several weeks/months before Gracie begins to warm up and open up to you. It maybe difficult for you emotionally because you will not understand why the process is taking so long given all of the love, please be understanding.  

Gracie may never be a social butterfly with all people as long as you can accept this, adopting and then watching a shy dog blossom into a loyal and loving pet is a gratifying and rewarding experience.

Gracie is up-to-date on her vaccinations and spayed. If you would like additional information and an application; please contact Delia at email address:  rubsch@sbcglobal.net          

Our rescue dogs come in all shapes, colors and sizes they love unconditionally they don’t judge and they’re extremely loving and loyal.  Rescue dogs form a lifelong bond with their families and are forever grateful for their new happy family and life

animal.description:
Secure, physical fence required. Home with another tolerant and playful dog required. Adopters must live within 30 miles of King of Prussia, PA. 
COTTON
Breed: Cocker spaniel/poodle mix
Gender: Female
Approximate DOB: 1/1/2015
Size: Medium
Weight (Potential):  15 (15)
Color: White/tan
Health: Visually impaired
Shedding: Moderate/Low
Grooming Needs: High
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Good with Dogs: Yes
Good with Cats: Unknown
Good with Children: Good with older children
Cost to adopt: $300

A secure, physical fence is required. Adopters must live within 30 miles of King of Prussia, PA.

Cotton was born in a Pennsylvania puppy mill and used for breeding from an early age. Despite being a productive breeder, she was passing her genetic eye condition down to her puppies so Finding Shelter volunteers were able to secure her freedom through educating the puppy mill operator. Cotton was filthy, shy, shut down and petrified when she was rescued, but she is becoming comfortable in her foster room and learning to enjoy the simple things in life, including toys. Once she learned that she could roam on the grass in the fenced yard and would be treated with love and kindness, she responded with joy and every day trusts her humans more every day. Cotton has cataracts and is taking daily drops from high eye pressure. She is expected to lose her vision completely at some point and could potentially lose her eyes if she develops severe glaucoma. But Cotton adjusts even though she bumps into things sometimes. She loves to play with other dogs and needs a resident dog companion. She is becoming a happy girl and can’t wait to find a loving and patient home where she can continue to flourish.

The first step is to submit an application at https://www.findingshelter.org/portfolio-items/cotton/

animal.description:
(The following dog is not with our rescue - this is a courtesy listing for his owner, Brandon - please contact Brandon Email: brandong512@gmail.com)


1. Age and weight
Hunter is 10 Years old and 6 months
2. Spayed/Neutered or not
Neutered
3. Vaccination status (rabies, DHLPP etc)
Up to date
4. Being wormed/flea/tick treated monthly?
Currently on Trifexis, monthly
5. Any medical issues (when did he/she last have a vet check up?)
Last vet check-up a month ago. Occasionally gets ear infections after baths (water got in his ear). We usually get prescribed ear drops and administer for a short period of time. Other than that healthy dog.
6. How does he/she behave around men/women/children/strangers/people on the street/other animals
When he is not familiar with the person he is very shy and reserved. There needs to be some kind of warming up period with a person that will allow him to get accustomed and use to the person. Generally he does better with new women than men, but he still needs a slow introduction to the new person. I’m not sure how he does with children, because we’ve never put him in an environment with kids. On the street, people cannot randomly pet him, because when he is unaware of a person around him, especially if it's a stranger, he can become startled, and possibly bite the person. He does pretty well with other dogs when slowly introduced in a controlled environment, but when startled he may bite.
7. Normal daily routine (food/exercise)
Food twice a day morning and night Daily walk 20-30 minutes.
8. Indoor or outdoor dog? (or both)
Both
9. Level of training (what commands does he/she know/how does he/she walk on leash/reaction to seeing other dogs when on leash)
Commands: Sit, paw, out, no, off.
 Usually towards the beginning of the walk he tugs and pulls on the leash a lot because he likes to smell everything around him. Afterwards he tends to relax, it also gets easier if using a dog non-invasive collar that tightens a little when he pulls. Sometimes he gets riled up and excited when he sees a dog and pulls (usually when another dog barks and starts acting sporadically) other than that he does pretty well just starts marking trees more often for a few seconds.
10. Any particular likes/dislikes (how is he/she about being handled/petted – any sensitive areas, like ears, feet etc.)
When pet he is sensitive on legs (especially both back legs), paws, and tail.
11. How does he/she react to riding in the car/going to the vet/can he/she be lifted
He does pretty well in the car. At the vet, however, he can get aggressive and so we give him sedatives a couple hours beforehand. At the vet they use a muzzle and everything usually goes well. He does not like to be lifted and could cause him to bite, unless he is sedated.
12. Has he/she ever bitten any other animals/people? If so, what was the severity and was medical action needed?
He has bitten one dog before, it was not severe, and there was little to no bleeding on the smaller dog. He has bitten people a few times before, the severity has varied. Sometimes his bites do not puncture the skin. The worst bite mark was when a construction worker got close to him while he was on a leash tied up to a rail, and he lashed out and bit the worker's leg. The bite mark broke the skin, and there was bleeding, the worker needed some stitches.
13. Any separation anxiety issues or other behavioural issues?
He has some kind of separation anxiety. When left out for too long he gets anxious. Behavior issues would include not reacting well to strangers, and not being socialized as well.
14. Where did you obtain the dog from and why are you attempting to rehome the dog now? How long have you owned the dog?
Obtained dog from a jindo breeder in Texas. We are rehoming because I primarily took care of him, but since I am moving out and he recently bit someone, my parents would no longer like to take care of him.
15. Have you contacted any other rescues for assistance?
No
16. What are the best methods of contact for people interested in either fostering or adopting your dog?
Email: brandong512@gmail.com

(Located in Los Angeles, CA 90024)

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Gracie Bess is an absolutely gorgeous girl! But of course we don't have to tell you that -- you can see for yourself in her photos. Gracie is a lively young girl who is safe with chickens and other livestock BUT she is not cut out for life in the pasture. She enjoys time outside, and that girl can find a mud puddle quicker than any other dog we have! But she prefers living close to her people instead of staying in the pasture with livestock.

Gracie is house/potty-trained and crate-trained. Her only bad habit in the house is that she's a stealthy counter-surfer, and since she's a tall girl, she has no trouble getting whatever she wants off the kitchen counter.

Gracie is quite the athlete and has no trouble clearing a 5' tall fence, so 6' tall fencing is a must for this pretty girl.

She gets along with other dogs (as you can see in some of her photos), but she plays rough. Some dogs don't like that, and will react negatively, which can lead to a fight. This has happened twice in her time with us. One female dog interpreted Gracie's play as an attack, and it turned into a fight that resulted in the other dog needing a trip to the vet to have several puncture wounds treated. When Gracie played too rough with another dog, he yelped and ran away, so that was the end of it. Gracie has ignored the small dogs in our home, so we're confident that she's not really a mean girl -- she just doesn't realize that her style of play is too rough for some dogs. A meet & greet will be really important if you have other dogs.

If Gracie sounds like the perfect match for your family, please visit our website to read about our adoption process and submit your application.
