animal.description:
Hi, my name is Colby!  I am an older boy, approximately 11 years old.  I came to HSJC from another shelter where I'd been surrendered by my people who could no longer care for me.

I'm a very sweet boy who has been getting some well-deserved TLC in foster care.  I adore my leash walks with my foster mom - I like to sniff everything!  I like to nap in a warm lap, and I like to lay in the sun.  My foster mom says I run around excitedly at mealtime, and I always remind her when it's dinner time (sometimes far before dinnertime).  In my previous home I did not appreciate small children, so I'm seeking a home with no kids under 10.  I do not like other doggies, and am looking to be the only dog in my new home (I DO NOT want to visit dog parks either)!

When I arrived, my teeth were all bad.  I only wanted to eat kibble at first (likely what I was used to), and my teeth actually moved as I ate.  :( My mouth was very painful and I just didn't feel very good.  I had all my bad teeth removed and am now on a diet of canned food (though I could eat kibble, but I can't chew it).  I also got neutered, micro-chipped, and caught up on my rabies and DAPP vaccines.  I have a grade 2-3 heart murmur.  This means anesthesia is riskier for me and exercise should be somewhat limited.  

Medical care for seniors like me - particularly dental procedures - are very costly.  If you're looking at me and you appreciate the care and attention I've gotten here at HSJC, please consider sponsoring me with a donation!

My adoption fee is $150 (+ $20 county dog license, if residing within Jefferson County).  IF YOU ARE SEEING MY BIO, I AM STILL UP FOR ADOPTION - PLEASE FOLLOW THE DIRECTIONS BELOW.

ADOPTION PROCEDURE: HSJC is currently CLOSED to the public due to the pandemic. We are accepting applications for Colby, and you can submit one via our website here: https://hsjcwa.org/adopt-a-dog
We do not ship animals, and due to COVID and border issues cannot adopt to Canada at this time.

If we find an applicant who seems to match Colby well, we will contact you to schedule a time for you to meet him at our facility. If you have trouble submitting your application, please send an inquiry and we can email you one!

animal.description:
Sophie will not be placed in a home with stairs, children or other dogs. She is around 10 years old and weighs 9 pounds. She is healthy as validated from a recent blood test and x-rays and her teeth were recently cleaned while spayed. She has a microchip as well. READ,READ, READ, please ----- Sophie can walk, more like a hobble, her rear legs do not bend so Sophie’s must be picked up to get up a small step. She loves lying on the sofa next to you when you are watching television, but you must pick her up and take her back down off the sofa. Sophie is not a dog that enjoys walks because she tires easily due to her back legs, however she would love being walked in a stroller and maybe walking a few feet for some exercise. She is an inside dog 100% of the time and is only taken out to go potty and you must wait for her to go she cannot be left outside. She is still learning to go potty but as long as you carry her outside on a regular basis, she does not potty in the house. She sleeps on the bed and can hold her potty all night. Sophie is a wonderful, sweet girl. She loves sleeping in the bed and lying on the couch watching TV.
Sophie was found on the side of the road by a Poochmatch volunteer. She is a senior dog. Her rear spine is fused together, probably from an accident and someone never sought veterinary care for her. Her injuries were left to heal on their own. Poor Sophie but let me tell you she is a sweetheart and has a wonderful temperament. Sophie is a special girl with special needs, she deserves to be spoiled, loved and cared for. Her adoption fee is $495 which covers the cost of her x-ray, spay, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), professional grooming, microchip and microchip registration. If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application, available on our website, poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab and please read the paragraphs below for more details on our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered.

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in, please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

animal.description:
Kenzy Kensington was saved from a family in Kensington. This lovely family first saw Kenzie running down the street when she was almost struck by a car. They stopped and Caught her and other passerby’s told them she lived right up the street and was loose often. They let Kenzie lead the way up to a home. Wanting to make sure she got in safe and sound they knocked on the door. Then gently told the man at the door, we just wanted to make sure she made it home - she almost got hit up the street. Then to their absolute surprise and shock the man who was once Kenzie’s father said that ain’t my problem we sent her out we got other dogs and we don’t need her keep her if you want to! Well this couple was horrified but said are you sure- well take her right now! And he said that’s great good luck goodnight and shut the door! WTF this nice couple was in no position to keep her permanently but they certainly weren’t gonna leave her out on the street, so take her home they did. They soon after reached out for help and we were happy to be able to step up! So our sweet girl has gotten the full veterinary package and is now getting doted on with her new foster brother. She is house trained, overall polite in the house, a very rough player. Not ready to share bones yet but low level toys don’t cause an issue. She is crate trained and loves it and will choose to take naps on the fluffy comforter inside. She’s friendly and approachable, Very strong on leash but seems like she’ll be easy to teach. I’d Love to see this girl living with another canine companion with a fenced in yard so she can get her energy out or with a family very dedicated to draining her energy with lots of walks, games, and exercise. 
She may be barely a year old and is ready to take a chance at a new start with a new family that would never let her down again. Can you be her second chance? 

Wants
Fenced yard
Playmate

Details
Hey there! Are you interested in a pup? All our dogs are dog friendly, kid friendly, and can be cat tested. They will be UTD medically and may have required return visits for more vet care based on their needs.
Kenzy $600
Spay neuter
Microchip
Rabies*1
Distemper* 1-4 
Lepto* 2
Heartworm test-pets over 6 months
Fecal exam
Deworming
Current on :Flea tick prevention and Heartworm prevention 
Starter food
Treats
Toy
Poop bag dispenser
30-45 min training session at your local petsmart
Exclusive petsmart Coupons including free over night stay in hotel and doggie day camp visit. 30% off first groom too! 
Access to Furever Family private fb group
*Collar Leash - if available 
Seasonal extras

Please note there is a $25 cancellation fee. 
If you do make an appt for a private meet and do not select a pet, a fee of $25 -30 mins or $50 - over 30 mins will apply for your private visit. 

To adopt contact Furever2016@gmail.com 
To get started send in pictures of your home and outdoor space. You will receive an application and a telephone interview. Then it’s time to meet our pets at their foster home- often in Ambler. On that day you will meet your pet and take them home for an in-home trial period. Just to make sure it’s a great fit for everyone! We require each adopter to join our private Facebook group Furever Family to keep in touch!

animal.description:
Meet Ike, an approximately 9-year-old, male, white Labrador/husky (?) who became a Misfit when his elderly caregiver had to enter an assisted-care facility in July 2020.

Since becoming a misfit, he’s lost 20 lbs and went from limping only half a block to actively walking around the entire neighborhood and even galloping.

Ike is neutered, up to date on all age-appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, heart-worm negative, and micro-chipped!

He is house trained and kennel trained. He has allergies which cause him to hack and sneeze and sometimes has snotty nose stringers.

He gets along with chickens, cats, and children. Does not like babies that can walk. He likes camping and is very obedient.

Ike gets a little yelpy when hugged suddenly from behind. I suspect that is due to failing hearing. He can hear, but I don’t think his hearing is what it once was. 

Ike is good at communicating his need to go outside and barks only twice when he’s ready to come back in.

He is very good on the leash so that there really isn’t a need for one. He’s very patient and affectionate. Also very gentle and sweet.

You can apply to meet/adopt Ike at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application.

[NOTE: We are a rescue NOT a shelter, meaning WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY THAT OPENS TO THE PUBLIC. Typically, an application and home visit (both of which are required for adoption) MUST be completed, BEFORE a potential adopter will be introduced to one of our pets, in order to first determine that our basic adoption requirements are met, prior to introductions being made. We also utilize personal reference and vet checks (to ensure that any pets already in the potential adoptive home are current on vaccines, heart worm prevention and sterilized) in our adoption process, all of which is intended to ensure that the best match, between pet and people, is made. The adoption fee is based on on the dog's age.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Taya! I was rescued, along with my 7 puppies from an animal shelter in Alabama before arriving at Big Dog Ranch & Rescue. I am a super sweet girl who loves everyone I meet but I may need a little bit of training in order to learn how to control my excitement. I love to play with other dogs, big or small. I have. a lot of energy and can be a jumper so I would probably do best in a home with children over the age of 12. I also have a strong prey drive and wouldn't like to cohabitate with cats or other small animals. I would be the best fit for an experienced dog owner who might know how to correct my excitable behavior and keep me focused. I am definitely a dog who needs to have a big yard to run around in and my energetic spirit would lend itself best to a busy home. I would like to learn how to behave in public so that I can go with my new family on lots of adventures. Some further training would absolutely be helpful in helping me to be the best dog that I can be for your family. I am already potty-trained and I love to go on leashed walks....maybe a little bit too much! I will never tire of playing fetch with you, enjoying my toys, or cuddling on the couch with my new favorite people.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Lady Marmalade was found in a secured backyard, where she'd been tossed over the block wall. Attached to the exterior gate was a hastily scrawled note that read, 'My name is Bobo, I need a home.'

Despite having been let down so cruelly and coldly by her previous humans, our little Lady is a loving and gentle soul. Though it, of course, took her a few days to feel comfortable, safe and begin to trust again, Marmalade has bounced back in a huge way!

Marmalade loves to cuddle with her humans, first and foremost. She enjoys the company of other dogs, and is beginning to play with her foster siblings. She doesn't seem to know what toys or chews are, but she sure does love her breakfast and dinner! Marmalade likes her crate, and finds comfort and security there when she's uncertain. She's also house trained in her foster home, and has been an absolute angel inside the home.

A note from foster mom: She will use both her paws at the same time to pull my hand far enough off my lap so she can rub against it to get me to pet her. She does not understand the concept of a leash or walk (yet!). Spinning in a circle is her go to happy dance!

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application. Because we expect a large number of applications, and are still understaffed due to COVID19, we will only be able to email those applicants that are approved to schedule a meet and greet. Thank you in advance for your understanding if you don't hear back from us regarding your application.
animal.name: Lady Marmalade

animal.description:
Chardonnay is a gorgeous & friendly Bulldog/Pitbull mix who is 1 year old and weighs 55 lbs. She recently lost her foster home due to no fault of her own and is in immediate need of a foster or adopter so that we can keep her out of boarding. Chardonnay has had professional training and is a loving, affectionate, intelligent girl who enjoys being with her people. She has low-med energy and would do great in a home with a fenced yard and a male, submissive dog. Her ideal person/family will be committed to continuing her training and offering her the leadership she needs to live her best life. She is housebroken, crate trained, spayed, fully vaccinated & microchipped. 

For more information about Chardonnay, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to foster or adopt sweet Chardonnay, please submit an application for her at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

Meet JoJo and Tink! These two sweet seniors (exact ages unknown) are looking for their forever home, together or separate. Both are very fun, easy going, clean in their crate, and get along great with other dogs in play groups. They love soft blankets and cozy time after a fun afternoon in their fenced yard. Tink is on a weight loss program and loves to hang out outside and go for adventures. Jojo is very fit and a full of fun. We think Jojo may be Tinks son (they came from the same home). 

JoJo and Tink require a fully fenced yard with a visible fence. Their adoption donations are $200 each or $350 for the pair.

PLEASE NOTE: If you are interested in meeting JoJo and/or Tink please answer the adoption application questions, please copy and paste (please do not put an attachment, we cannot view attachments) these answers into facebook messenger, due to COVID leaving us short staffed, we are not on email. Any application sent to email runs a high risk of not being seen. Adoption application is located here: http://www.rescueeverydog.org/Adoption.php 

JOJO AND TINK ARE IN FOSTER CARE IN POULSBO, WA. MEET AND GREETS WILL TAKE PLACE THERE AS WELL.



Mandatory fenced yard. No apartments. Some Condos and homes with a private use fenced yard maybe considered. No children under 8 years of age. Donations cover some of the care costs for R.E.D. animals. Like housing, supportive care, medical needs and food. All R.E.D. animals are spayed or neutered and vaccinated. Most are micro chipped with adopter registration included. R.E.D. is a 501 C3 and all donations support our life saving missions. For more information and to complete the on line adoption application on R.E.D., please, see our website at www.rescueeverydog.org. 
PLEASE READ ALL OF THE FOLLOWING TO APPLY TO ADOPT: Not all applicants will be approved for requested animals. R.E.D. reserves the right to refuse service and adoption without explanation. R.E.D. is the companion animal's advocate and will select the most suitably matched home/environment for the the companion animals emotional needs and management requirements based on each companion animal's breed(s) general needs and the unique needs of each individual animal in our care. R.E.D. requires all applicants and adopters to conduct themselves in a respectful and courteous manner. R.E.D. updates it animals adoption postings daily. If you wish to apply to adopt this companion animal go to the on line application at R.E.D.'s website www.rescueeverydog.org. and look under adoption. Before applying, please, read the following information. 
(1) Application, Phone interview, Home visit are required. Adoption Donations are generally $100.00. to 450.00 or as posted. Donations support R.E.D.'s life saving missions and medical and other care given.(2) R.E.D. Dogs are spayed or neutered prior to adoption, vaccinated for Parvo Distemper and generally are micro chipped. (3) You must be at least 18 years of age to complete the application or to apply to adopt a companion animal. For the safety of children and dogs and limited information on dog the dogs interaction with children- R.E.D generally prefers/requires children in adoptive home to be approximately 5 or 6 years of age and up unless otherwise noted in the dog profile. All children must be behavior appropriate with animals. (4) R.E.D. does not a ship animals to out of state adopters. Out of state adopters must come to meet the animal in person in Washington if approved for a meet and greet with a R.E.D. companion animal. Thank you.

animal.description:
**WE ARE CURRENTLY DOING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. YOU MUST CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING. PLEASE LEAVE US A VOICEMAIL IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO REACH US. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE AND UNDERSTANDING.- CCDP STAFF**

Hi there. My name is King. I'm about 3 years old and I weigh about 45 lbs. 
I was left here in a kennel at the pound overnight one night. My owner left me here with a note that said "His name is King". Nothing more. When I first arrived, I had horrible entropion which made my very sore. The pound had the surgery on my eyes and I am feeling so much better and I'm much happier. I do still have a little cloudiness in my left eye from ulceration and scarring from my entropion, but it is healed and no longer painful. 
I can be a little timid and unsure of new people at first, but once I get to know you, I am very sweet and loving. I listen pretty well and I love to cuddle. 
I do okay with some other dogs, but I definitely need to meet any other dog(s) that I would potentially live with, prior to being adopted, to make sure I like them.
If you're looking for a nice dog to add to your family, please consider adopting me.

Our adoption fee is $150.00. The pound DOES NOT accept checks for adoption fees. We're able to accept cash for adoption OR Visa/ Mastercard/ Discover Card. A convenience fee of 2.39% will be applied to all credit/ debit card adoptions. If you intend to do a foster-to-adopt, the fee must be cash. ALL dogs/puppies adopted from our shelter will receive their parvo distemper vaccine, bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine (if aged at 12 weeks or older), be dewormed with a 3 day course of panacur dewormer, be microchipped, receive their current Ohio dog license and will be spayed or neutered. ALL DOGS/PUPPIES WILL BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED unless a health issue prohibits the surgery from being performed. Not all dogs posted for adoption are spayed/ neutered yet. If you're driving a long distance to adopt, please verify that the vetting process has been completed and dog you're interested in adopting is still available for adoption. The above mentioned vetting is all included in your adoption fee. The adoption fee and what is included in the adoption fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE.

Adoptions MUST be done at the pound and in person as there is paperwork to fill out and an adoption contract that must be signed by the adopter. This means you must be willing to travel to our shelter to adopt.

IF the dog you're interested in adopting has medical conditions or injuries which require medical treatment, we ask that you help with the medical bills so we can continue to help the dogs coming in who need additional vet care.
We are a county run shelter, therefore we cannot control our intake or the health or behavior of the dogs that come in to our shelter.

Although we try our hardest to place all of our adoptable dogs, there are certain circumstances in which any dog in our care could be euthanized at any time and without further notice (IE: sudden untreatable medical condition or injury, temperament or behavioral problems which may not be apparent when the dog first arrives, lack or space, etc.), therefore all dogs at our shelter should be considered urgent. The adoption of a more highly adoptable dog will mean more time for the less adoptable dog in the kennel next to him!

Shelter hours are: Monday-Friday: 8 am- 4 pm
Saturday: 8 am - 11 am.
Sunday: 8 am - 11 am.
Adoptions are always welcome during hours of operation. We will make special arrangements for adoptions in advance.
There is nobody in the office on Saturday and Sunday, so therefore we are unable to answer or return phone calls over the weekend.

Can't adopt a dog? We would love to have more volunteers who are able to spend time with our dogs! The dogs LOVE going for walks and the socialization and exercise helps make the dogs more adoptable.

Contact information:
8455 County Home Road
Lisbon, OH 44432
(330)424-6663
Email: hpecorelli@ccclerk.org

animal.description:
Please welcome Bowie to our rescue !! Bowie is 9 months old and he was on his way to a shelter until the owners were convinced to let him go to rescue. Bowie definitely needs someone who can continue to work with him on his basic commands, manners, and potty training.

He is crate trained and voluntarily goes into the crate. He needs a husky experienced home with a 6ft fence, and he needs a home who can provide structure. Bowie is great with all people, and thanks to training he is now very dog friendly.  Bowie loves to be around other big dogs and he loves to play. 

Bowie went through two weeks of obedience training to work on his socialization and to build up his confidence on the leash. Bowie used to be very scared of cars and other distractions while he is on walks. With training, he has made great progress but he is still going to need a home who can continue to work on his socialization as well as building up his confidence on the leash. Bowie also needs a home with no small children.  He needs a strong owner who can help him grow.

animal.description:
**** SPECIAL NEEDS ********

All Hail King Louie! A regal and majestic addition to the Boston Buddies Royal Family. Louie was banished from his original kingdom when his family felt they were no longer able to provide Louie the life style & care he requires. Louie came to Boston Buddies with severely inflamed skin, infected ears, hair loss, hind end weakness & urinary incontinence. To figure out what the heck was going on, Louie was whisked off to the Veterinary Specialty Hospital for an evaluation. First he met with the Neurologist and underwent a MRI. The MRI identified 3 disk herniations. The doctor confirmed that too much time has passed since his initial injury so sadly Louie is a not a good candidate for surgery. Louie will not regain full control of his bladder or bowels so he will need to be expressed, wear a belly band or diaper and have easy access to a yard. Physical Therapy and acupuncture were recommended to help him build and maintain strength in his back legs. Our handsome dignitary went to see the Dermatologist for assistance with his skin issues. He eats a Royal Canin prescription diet and gets weekly medicated baths. His majesty's skin is looking much better and you can tell he feels much better too. This 8 year old, 25 pounds French Aristocrat loves stuffed toys, other dogs (except the ones on TV), people and meal time. A little hind end weakness doesn't stop this dignified dog from visiting his royal subjects. He struts around with is head held high. Sometimes he travels on foot, sometimes he travels in his prestigious mobile device (doggie wheelchair) or in his royal carriage (doggie stroller). Louie came into rescue without the family jewels (meaning he was already neutered), he is up to date on vaccines and microchipped. If you are looking to upgrade your social status and want welcome a very special pooch into your castle, report to our website @ https://www.bostonbuddies.org/adoption-application/ and complete an adoption application.

View more pictures on our facebook page - facebook.com/BostonBuddiesInc

Adoption Donation is $200.00

animal.description:
Katie is just a little old girl who loves to snuggle an chill out on the couch. She’s very mellow and happy when she’s comfortable and loves to sunbath outside! She’s sassy old lady who is very talkative too! She lets you know when she needs to go outside with a little howl and her favorite treats are chicken bits! Our vet believes she was born in 2010.

Included with adoption: Age-appropriate vaccinations, up to date heart-worm preventative, heart-worm test if over 6 months, insurance for 30 days, microchip with registration, and spayed or neutered- if not already, a voucher is provided.

animal.description:
Lola is 1.5 years old and 52 lbs. Good with dogs and kids over 12. Must have other dog in the home of similar size and secure fenced yard.

Meet Lola! This wonderful girl was part of a litter of puppies born on a rural property. The pups were not socialized or handled by humans when they were little. As a result, Lola is shy with humans but now is much more comfortable. Her temperament is just wonderful. She is kind and funny and just a goofy puppy. She loves affection and lives for belly rubs. She is eager to learn and eager to please.

Lola is more confident every day and is a lovely pup that will continue to blossom if you are willing to work with her to gain confidence. She is nearly there! She is learning to walk on a leash and is getting the hang of it - the world is a bit scary to her still. She is starting to really enjoy her time sniffing around on walks.

Lola does not have a mean bone in her body, but living with young kids is probably a bit stressful for her. She cannot live with cats. Lola is quite bonded to her sister, Louise, who is also with us, so in order to thrive in a new home, she will need another dog pal to live with her. Alternatively she and Louise can be adopted together. They do love each other.

We would like to see her in a more residential neighborhood rather than a busy part of town.

She is now updated on all shots, spayed, and chipped.

Her adoption fee is $495 and you can submit an application via savinggreatanimals.org

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description: SKYLAR Is a three-year-old husky who was found as a stray in Baltimore. Being bred to run across the frozen tundra, he does like to test his boundaries so a secure fence and lots of exercise is a must for this guy! He does easily let us hook a leash to his collar but was a little mouthy with the volunteers at the shelter where we got him from when they were putting on and off a slip lead over his head. He was very polite about it and didn’t bite down but because of this we prefer him to have a home without small children. We would love Skylar to go to a family with husky experience! He is scheduled to be neutered on November 3 and will be available after he recovers from his surgery. Skylar will also be vaccinated, heartworm tested and microchipped. animal.description:
**ADOPTION APPLICATION REQUIRED via our website Rarerescue.org**

ADOPTION FEES: Our Adoption Fees vary based on adoptability to help all of the animals in our organization. Please make sure to read the adoption fee below in the bio.

BREEDS: We are not breed experts. The breed(s) listed for each adoptable are best guesses or suggestions.

STEPS TO ADOPT:

Read the adoptable’s bio below, including their adoption fee

Read  ADOPTION PROCESS page under the "Adopt" section

Complete the  DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION (located on our website RARErescue.org)

*Applications will be attended to before general inquiries. We may or may not have time to respond to general inquiries if you have not submitted an application.

We understand that it is important to you to find the right fit for your family. We feel the same way! The application is important and necessary for this reason. 

All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption

BASIC INFORMATION:

Suggested Breed(s): Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Male/Neutered
Approx. Age or D.O.B: 4-5 years
Approx. Weight: 80 lbs
Coat Type: Short
Good around most dogs: Yes
Good around most cats: Yes
Energy Level: Medium
Fence yard may be required: Yes
Any other specifics:  Rudy is a lover and a charmer! He is being fostered with his good friend Dixie, the light brown brindle dog in his pictures. His foster mom also has dogs of her own and they all get along very well. Rudy would prefer to be in a more quiet household without a lot of loud noises. He loves people, but can be scared by a lot of fast movement, so a person or family without small children would love to spoil on Rudy and make him their cuddle buddy! He will ask for belly rubs and loves to cuddle. Once you meet Rudy, you won't be able to stop yourself from falling in love!   *Note - in case you are looking for a pair, Rudy and Dixie are great buddies and their adoption fees would be discounted if adopted together. But they are also fine with being adopted separately as well. 

Will you be a Hero in Rudy's story?

Visit our website/Click on Adopt to APPLY today!  RARErescue.org

Adoption Fee: $185.00



Please REMEMBER, All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption



PLEASE NOTE: We are a non-profit organization without municipal or government funding. Veterinary/Medical expenses are constant for an animal rescue. Our adoption fees not only help to provide vetting and care for the animal being adopted, but they also help to cover heartworm treatments and other treatable ailments that many animals, that would otherwise be euthanized, need in order to be made available for adoption.



Please understand that adopting an animal is a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to that animal and there will be veterinary expenses throughout their life that can often cost several hundreds, if not thousands of dollars (without pet insurance), especially without annual checkups and preventative care.  As a potential family for this pet you are responsible for their safety and that includes keeping them on your property.

***If you are not in the middle Tennessee area, transport can potentially be arranged to approved homes, depending on distance and local adaptability. We normally do not allow adoptions outside of 1.5 hours driving distance.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, foster, or aid in the rescue efforts of RARE!

animal.description:
Princess Penelope is a 1 year old Boston Terrier that weighs about 14lbs. She is spayed, microchipped, up to date on all of her vaccinations, and on heart worm prevention.

Princess Penelope is a sweet girl that is very friendly with everyone she meets! She was born with a condition called spina bifida, which causes her fecal and urinary incontinence, as well as occasional mild weakness in her hind legs which is almost unnoticeable. Although this will be a lifelong diagnosis for her, her condition is very manageable and her quality of life is still great. She wears a diaper in her foster home and doesnt seem to mind. Keeping her on a strict diet of her dog food helps manage the incontinence issues. Daily expression of her bladder and monitoring for signs of UTI are also an important part of her care. You would never know Princess Penelope is a special needs dog from the way she runs and plays! She loves to be around children, and does well with cats and other dogs. She walks well on leash and will come to her foster mom when called. She is an affectionate girl that likes to cuddle up after playing. 

If you would like to give Princess Penelope her forever home, please submit an application at southerncrossbtr.com. Her adoption fee is $375. She is being fostered in Lafayette, IN area. If you have specific questions about Princess Penelope that are not addressed in her bio, please reach out to her foster home at ddscanlon@gmail.com.

For a complete listing of all of our available Bostons, or to learn more about SCBTR, please visit our website at www.southerncrossbtr.com. You can also find and follow us on Facebook at facebook.com/southerncrossbtr. Thank you 
 for choosing rescue and for considering Southern Cross for your next furbaby.

 ** IF THIS AD IS STILL ACTIVE, THEN THIS PET IS STILL AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION **

He was scheduled to be euthanized at an overcrowded shelter because his stray hold was up and there was no more room to house him, but fortunately, BarkVille was able to save him before his time ran out.  Wagner's foster mom says he is gorgeous, sweet, curious, loves car rides and would be fine in a home with or without other dogs. He has a confident dog with a strong personality so slow introductions to other dogs would be required.  He is a playful, intelligent, energetic boy who needs a fenced yard (6 ft high at least cuz this boy can jump) and an experienced, active owner with a firm hand to give him structure & guidance. He has terrible leash manners (still a work in progress), but he is young, smart & treat motivated which makes him highly trainable!  He is housebroken, crate trained, neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped.

For more information about Wagner, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt sweet Wagner, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

Lilo is a low rider with a big heart.  Her pictures don't do her squishy face justice.  She's a tiny girl with a lot of love to give.

animal.description:
Preference is being given to Boulder County area and to a home with a friendly, confident dog to be a mentor for Foxy.  In addition a fence is almost certainly a must (rare exception made here). Thanks for your interest!!! Also, no condos, townhomes, apartments.
*Foxy is finishing up heartworm treatment. We expect her to be heartworm free by July. Her treatment goes with her and SDR will support her heartworm treatment costs until she tests negative. 

-------------------------------------- 

Hello, My name is FOXY... not only do I look like a fox, I'm quick and smart like one, too. My foster dad calls me Foxy Bear as I zoom around my yard! I am only 30 lbs, which is a perfect size for a Colorado dog. I am looking for a gentle and kind person to show me the wonderful  life I deserve. 

I love playing with my foster brother who is twice as big as me. I would do better in a home with a resident dog like him to show me the way! In fact, I think it is a must. 

I also love food! I'll do almost anything for a food reward. My foster dad has taught me to sit, shake, and touch his hand already. I'm starting to learn about a "clicker"... I know it means I did something good and a tasty treat is coming.

My favorite place to hang out is on the big bed. I've slept there with my new family every night since I arrived, and I like to nap there when we're not busy. If I'm bored and want some attention, I go into my foster dad's office and give him a gentle nudge with my nose. If I sit nice with my tail wagging, I usually get some pets and sometimes even a treat.

I also like to hang out in the yard when it is nice outside. Usually, I just nap in the grass or watch whatever is going on. My yard has to have a pretty good fence.

I am a little slow to warm up to new people when we first meet, but if you give me time I quickly am your friend, too!  *Foxy is not a brew pub dog, nor will she be a farmer's market girl if they ever start back up again. She needs a more quiet home with a loving person. 

I'm also friends with every dog I've met so far. My big foster brother is fun, and we greet a bunch of neighbor dogs hanging out in their yards when we go for walks. But, squirrels are absolutely fun to chase! And rabbits too! So, be assured that I'll keep them away from you and our home.

I really like my coat... it gives me a nice warm hug when it is cold outside.

Speaking of rough life, it turns out I came down with something called "heartworm" while at the shelter this summer. It doesn't really bother me and it isn't catchy for other dogs this time of year, but everybody says it is bad so we are trying to fix it. Right now, I get an extra treat every morning and evening. My foster dad calls it "medicine", but it tastes like turkey to me and I gobble it up. In a month or so. SDR is committed to paying for all of Foxy's heartworm treatment until she tests negative! 

Here are some details about me according to SDR: I'm a 1-1/2 year old Shepherd/Sheltie mix female born 5-1-2019. I'm spayed, microchipped, housetrained and up to date on my doggie shots. I'm on heartworm treatment and soon I'll be good as new.. 

I’m working with a wonderful behavior consultant named Elisheba Fey, and she is helping me become more confident! 

I really like when new people gently toss treats next to me instead of staring at me and calling my name, or making me come to you for a treat. This protocol is called "treat and retreat" and used by the best dog trainers in the world. It makes the process of me trusting you, so much faster! And we will soon be buds if you can just follow this protocol! 
 Included in my adoption fee is a session with Elisheba, so you can learn what we are learning! https://www.artandscience.dog/

For more info and/or to apply to adopt me, go to SummitDogRescue.org, fill out an application and send it in. A nice volunteer from SDR will get back to you as soon as they can.

animal.description:
Danni is a 5½-year-old American Staffordshire Terrier. This girl came into foster care after sitting in the shelter for about 60 days. She was lost, confused, lonely and it looked like she JUST HAD a litter of puppies. When she woke up the next day, the foster mom noticed her tummy looked a little different. She was taken the next day to the vet and it was confirmed SHE WAS pregnant! She had 3 healthy puppies the following week. She was the best mamma dog to her babies. She loved and cared for them dearly.

Danni is quiet and loves her person. She is affectionate, gives kisses and likes to snuggle. She is food motivated and is learning the "Sit", "Down", and "Place" commands. She is active, playful and likes to run in-yard. She is good with other dogs and people but we don't know yet about children.

She is  house- and crate-trained. She came to us heartworm positive and had to wait until after nursing to go thru the aggressive treatment. She has now finished her treatment and is looking for her furrever home just as her babies have. She is fully vetted, spayed and microchipped.

Please visit Regard4Life Animal Rescue at Petsmart in Longview on Saturdays for more information. You can also review our adoption album at http://Regard4Life.org or email regard4life.info@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Kate recently lost her family and needs a new one. She is a sweet girl who loves to give hugs and kisses if you let her. She is spayed, up to date on vaccinations and negative for heartworm disease. Kate will be a loyal family member and really wants a yard to run in so she no longer has to be in puppy prison. When she lost her family, she had to go outside to an aunt's house and was living in a small pen with a barrel house and very little companionship. She misses her people and their rambuctious children and the comforts of a home - beds and couches and little people to love her and give cuddles. We want the best for her and want to help her find a home! Because we are foster based, we require an approved application before a meet and greet can be scheduled. We think that is fair for our fosters, so every meet and greet has the potential to result in an immediate adoption. The application is available on the rescue website and can be completed online. We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.

animal.description: Housetrained? Yes. Experience with dogs? Yes.Resource guarding is possible, also possibly dog selective. Experience with cats/kids? History states he's not good with cats. Unknown how he is w/kids/ Here is what my foster mom had to say about me! Saddles has worked very well with me on leash. Very responsive to chicken and is able to walk very appropriately. He will sometimes lunge and bark when walking head-on towards another dog. He is crated at night and when he is home alone. He never complains and seems quite relaxed and comfy. He also knows: sit, down, shake, wait, take it, leave it, stay, back (aka go away), off, hoop (he loves jumping through a hoola hoop), heel, and more. Saddles arrived at the shelter as a stray. A kind person picked him up intending to keep him. The problem was, he didn't get along with the cat. They brought him to PACC where his behavior was deteriorating after being there for almost 2 months. Once I brought him home as a foster pet, his personality really came out! He is super affectionate, he loves to give hugs and kisses. He will also happily roll on his back to get belly pets. He is playful, mostly likes tug ropes, tennis balls for fetch, and his favorite toy is a plushy with a squeaker. Although he loves to play, he is on the lazier side, he just always wants to be pet! Saddle is the perfect combination of smart, lazy and a people-pleaser. He picks up basic commands like a wizard. He will also do things like put his tennis ball on the coffee table! He's lazy because most of the time, he likes to lay down in the sun that shines through the window and sleep. He shows us he's a people-pleaser by always coming when you call him. He also shows us that by listening intently to our voices on walks and during training. He's always willing to cuddle when we are. His best quality is that he's a great listener. He makes an excellent companion! My favorite behavior of his is when he gently puts his paws on my legs when I'm sitting on the couch. They are the gentlest hugs. Saddles would do best in a calm environment where he has a good day to day routine. His ideal owners would spend time reinforcing his training and take him for daily walks. He might even enjoy some sort of dog-sports to stimulate that mind of his!I think he enjoys being the only dog of the house but adopters need to be mindful of resource guarding if he is around other dogs. EMAIL PACC.FOSTER@PIMA.GOV to learn more!

NBSPCA license #0082


Wahlberg came to DunRoamin' Stray and Rescue on October 5th 2020 after his owner had passed away and he was no longer able to be cared for. He is a bright, handsome, sweet, senior black Labrador. The transition to a foster home was definitely a big change for this 14 year old boy, but his happy demeanor helped him settle in no time.

Wahlberg gets along great with other dogs but sometimes trips over smaller animals when he is excited and doesn't notice them. He is very respectful of cats, especially if he thinks they might deliver a swat! Wahlberg is definitely a people dog, preferring the company of humans over anything else. His hiking days are behind him, but he is always up for a cuddle on the couch or to lend a supportive ear.

Wahlberg is on medication for arthritis but he gets around fine. H would do best i a home with older children. He is kennel trained but does well loose in the house for short periods of time. He is an amazing boy who would be a great addition to a home. Please fill out an application for  Wahlberg here: https://form.jotform.ca/60793520585259

Adoption fee on this dog is $300.

		Zoey May is a 2-3 year old pretty black and red Shepherd.  She came into the shelter with a fractured back leg.  Her leg has been surgically repaired and she is now going on her sixth week of recovery.  No running or jumping for Zoey until November 14 when she has a recheck and should be able to return to normal dog activities.

		Zoey lives in a multi-dog home and gets along with her both the males and females in her foster home.  You can tell she wants to play with her dog buddies, so longer term she would probably like a dog buddy to play with.  Zoey has been a little snarky with the young female in the home.  She corrects very easily, but should be the only female in her forever home.

		Zoey is housebroken and can sleep in a crate, or is trustworthy sleeping free on her bed.  Because of her leg, Zoey is in a large kennel while her people are at work, she protests for a bit, then will settle.  Zoey become very attached to her people and would love a home with someone home most of the time.

		Zoey is a great girl who is curious, and very engaging.  Continued socialization and training will help her become her best self.  She will make a great addition for the right family. 

		Cats and other small furry critters unknown.

This dog is a Level 2. Please be sure you understand what a dog of this Level requires. Go to our home page for an explanation of the Dog Rating Levels.

For more information and to see when this dog will be attending an Adoption Day, please see our Dogs page on our main website at www.gcgsr.org. 

We operate within a reasonable driving distance from the Greater Sacramento area, the 	Central Valley down to Merced, and Lake Tahoe. A reasonable driving distance is determined by where one of our volunteers is willing to drive within our areas of service. That means we don't adopt out of our area, to Southern California, or Out of State. 


Thank you for visiting!

animal.description: Rae is a sweet and silly lady with the silkiest fur and squishiest face! She can be nervous at first with new people. However, Rae forms a strong bond with the people she knows and is very attentive to their emotional needs. She absolutely loves to chase soccer balls in the yard and could play forever! Rae can be jumpy and is very vocal at times as well, especially during playtime. Rae would be best in a home with older children (12+) who know how to respect her boundaries. She is able to co-exist with dogs in the play yard, but she is quick to tell them to get out of her space and isn't terribly interested in playing. She would likely prefer to be an only dog. Rae has seen our office cat many times in the lobby and after the initial excitement, she has decided to ignore his existence, so she may be able to live with cats. She will make a wonderful companion and will alert you if someone comes to your door!

animal.description:
Meet ZEKE, a profoundly handsome Blue Nose Pit Bull. 

Zeke was homeless, hungry, abused, defeated and extremely heartworm positive. Luckily, he was found by a Texas Animal Society (TAS) foster that gave him a soft bed, good food and lots of love. After an extensive search to find his people, Zeke became part of the TAS family. Once he started trusting again, he was bathed, nails trimmed and off to the vet he went. Zeke was fully vetted and x-rays were done to show the extent of his heartworms, which had already migrated into his lungs. We were devastated! The 3 shot fast kill treatment was started, only to end after the first shot. Zeke's poor body couldn't handle it and he became very ill. Everyone agreed to move him to the slow kill method. That was okay with his foster family because he was no longer on crate rest and able to run & play with all the pups in his foster home! 
Zeke is the most loving dog you'll meet. He absolutely adores his human and is so willing to please. He wants to be pet or get a belly rub 24/7! Zeke is shy, timid and confused at new things and/or people but wants to trust and recovers nicely. He is approx 5 years old but a BIG puppy! He plays hard, sleeps hard and drools like a St. Bernard! Zeke is unaware of his surroundings, aka...Bull in a China Cabinet...just full speed ahead when he's in go mode!! He does spend a lot of time relaxing, sunbathing or under the patio fans. Zeke likes a constant temperature of 71, so here in South Texas, he is mostly an inside dog. He loves to chew on bones and carry shoes around but they are never damaged! He truly is a gentle giant!
This love bug will do best in a home with an experienced dog owner that understands Pit Bulls; his size and power. So NO small dogs, NO small children, NO cats and he does best with female dogs. This list could change as he settles into his new home but to start these are the requirements. Zeke is crate trained but does exhibits some separation anxiety. He is leash trained, loads & rides in a car well, has good food manners and is easy to bathe & trim his nails. He knows some basic command and how to fetch, although not perfect at these, he tries. Zeke needs a loving, patient home with people that will spend a LOT of time with him. He will need people that are diligent about administering his monthly heartworm meds to get him free and clear of these deadly parasites. Zeke has never shown any aggression to people or dogs. He is definitely a lover! Zeke will make a loving addition to the right family! Will that be you?Interested in adopting a companion dog or cat from Texas Animal Society?
Please email info@texasanimalsociety.com and complete online adoption application at texasanimalsociety.org
Come visit our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/www.texasanimalsociety.org/

animal.description:
Missee Lee is an 8 year old pittie mix that is about 60lbs- she is laid back and just goes with the flow! She has impeccable manners in the home. Even though she would love to cuddle you all the time, she will wait for you to invite her on the couch or bed. While she waits for her personal invitation to join you or to be by your side, Missee will sleep on her bed & will wait until you are ready to take her out for a walk.  She's a quiet dog, house broken, & has a hearty appetite. Fearless and confident, Missee is a tough little chick with a frosty face and plenty of pep still left in her step! Dont let her age fool you!

When we agreed to take her, she was at the city shelter for 260 days! Most of this time, fortunately, was in a foster home, which she remains in with us. 
Missee is a sweet and well behaved girl. Unfortunately, she was plagued with severe ear infections. For 7 months, nothing helped. Her pain persisted and the swelling was unbearable. Finally, she received surgery to correct the issue. This care was possible with a private donor, a friend of the foster mom’s, who was her cheerleader since she was at the shelter. Missee is also allergic to a great many things, which everyone ignored until she entered foster care.

After healing from her surgery to open up the ear canal and a partial ear oblation, Missee is now ready for her forever home! Missee is also working with our trainer on manners. As she starts to feel better, her personality is really shining through. We learned that Missee loves other dogs, dressing up in clothes, and going for walks. Missee will pull towards any dog she can meet. Unfortunately, sometimes her approach is not well received, but she means well! She is a strong little tug boat and should be with someone that will continue working with her on training and manners. Missee is a dream in the home, house broken, and loves those who care for her! 

Missee would love a home that will continue to let her flourish. She asks that her forever home have no cats, but dogs are loved and welcomed! Our angel is a lower energy dog, so a mellow home is ideal! She howls with joy when happy and makes the funniest sound when you rub her belly. It's almost a purr! 
The ideal home should know that her ear issues likely stemmed from years of neglected energy. She should be on a poultry and potato free diet. 

If interested in adopting, email us at twentypawsrescue@gmail.com or info@twentypawsrescue.com. Please note that due to an email glitch, sometimes emails get lost. We respond to all emails! So, If you do not hear from us, please follow up!
animal.name: Missee Lee

animal.description:
****PETronus Rescue endeavors to include all pertinent information for each of the dogs within our organization with regard to approximate age, potty training status, kennel training status, temperament, activity level, dog/cat friendliness, etc in an effort to give those considering adopting as much information as we have.  Inquiries requesting additional information will not be returned, due to limited volunteers. Thank you for your understanding **** 

Meet Milo.

Milo was pulled with 2 of his siblings after being surrendered to the shelter because they had “too many”. They were very young and malnourished. 

Milo is now approximately a year old and healthy, has received vaccinations, and is neutered and microchipped. Milo would do best in an active home with no other dogs, or with a strong handler if there are other dogs in the home. He can be good and play with other dogs, but Milo lacks confidence and will growl, bark, and lunge during the initial meeting. If you are confident and comfortable with dog behavior and socialization, we would consider your application to adopt Milo if you have other dogs. 

Milo is a very active guy and needs to be adopted into a home with a yard, and preferably a pool as he LOVES to swim!

All PETronus Rescue dogs receive basic vaccinations (distemper/parvo, bordetella, & rabies), spay/ neuter, and microchip prior to adoption. We also treat any know medical issues, including heartworms.

Our dogs live in foster homes while they wait patiently for their forever families to find them. This is beneficial in that they learn house manners, crate training, housebreaking, etc while they wait and we are also able to get a very realistic picture of their energy level, temperament, etc so that we can place them in a home that is the best fit.

Our adoption fees are $200 for dogs over 1 year of age and $250 for dogs under 1 year of age. Puppies receive 3 rounds of puppy vaccinations.

If you are interested in adopting one of our amazing dogs, please fill out our adoption application here http://bit.ly/PRAdoption and we will be in touch!

animal.description:
OUR ADOPTION PROCESS AND APPLICATION ARE AVAILABLE AT WWW.SOHODOGRESCUE.ORG AND OUR FEE IS $275

Sherlock is a wonderful, medium-energy Australian Shepherd who is ready for his forever home! Sherlock is about 2 years old and has a gorgeous black dilute coat with copper and white trim, and a natural half tail. He weighs about 45 lbs and is house-trained, crate trained, knows his basic obedience commands and is quite food motivated! Sherlock enjoys riding in the car and walks pretty well on the leash.

Sherlock is a total lovebug to women and is learning to trust men. He is a very high Velcro guy and wants to be with you pretty much 24/7. He loves being in the midst of the action and pretty much being underfoot! He is typical of Aussies in that he is incredibly devoted and attached to his people - he loves being with them and hanging out on the couch, going for walks, or being underfoot when you are cooking. He also enjoys the company of other dogs and would do best in a home with at least one other confident, playful female dog to emulate. He has been tested with cats but is a little too interested in them for comfort - his best home will not have cats as he fixates on them. 

Sherlock's ideal home is either a quiet suburb or a rural area, as he gets pretty excited when he sees a lot of traffic. He is a medium energy guy that loves a good hike, but doesn't need a 5 mile run to keep him happy. He doesn't love men right away but adores women, and would do best in a home without young children as he seems to do best in a quieter home. He has good recall but because of his shyness, his foster family recommends a home with a physical fence just in case he gets spooked. He is extremely intelligent and loves to learn, and his favorite spot is curled up beside your bed at night. He would do great in a home with someone experienced with training shy dogs to help him reach his full potential. If this guy has stolen your heart like he's stolen ours, apply today at www.sohodogrescue.org!

animal.description:
Plum is a 4 year old 60 lb blonde cutie! She had a really harsh life before and came with a highly concerning behavior evaluation from the city shelter, which made her rescue only. Since she was a stray, her past is unknown. One of our experienced foster homes stepped up and offered to give her a chance! Before coming to us, Plum was a dog that didn't allow humans near her. Now, she is beautifully coming out of her shell! Plum is truly a dose of bunny eared perfection. 

After completing behavioral rehab and recovering from kennel cough in her foster home, Plum emerged an absolute sweetheart. Plum still requires a slow approach when meeting new people, though. Just give her a day or 2 to learn you are her friend and she's sugar, spice, and everything nice! Plum loves car rides, hikes, frolicing in the park, and meeting other dogs. Generally, she LOVES to play with them, but can be overwhelming to some. For this reason, she should be paired to tolerant and playful dogs in her forever home. Plum would love to be your only pet as well, so don't worry if you have no other pets at home. She loves to be your only shining star. 

Plum loves to jump into your lap and solicit pets. She is also a great student and attends online school with her foster sister. She is all about safety and virtual schooling! She would be a good candidate for an adult only home or one with older children that understand a patient and slow approach. 

Our little Plum is extremely receptive to training and positive reinforcement. Will you be the right one for Plum? She will return your love with so much kindness, warmth, and wiggles. 
If interested in adopting, please email us at twentypawsrescue@gmail.com or info@twentypawsrescue.com. Please note we respond to all emails. If you do not hear back from us, please follow up! Sometimes, emails get lost in cyberspace.

animal.description:
**********************



Dixie is a sweet Southern belle who was abandoned in Louisiana with a wound around her neck from an ill-fitting chain or collar.  She appears to be a Catahoula Leopard Dog mix (the state dog of Louisiana) with a striking specked coat and her left eye is half blue/half brown.  As of late October, Dixie is around 9 months old and 35 lbs. 

Her foster mom says, “Dixie is a very sweet and affectionate dog who loves everyone she comes in contact with.  She loves kids, other dogs and even responded well to a very dog friendly cat in the neighborhood.  Based upon that interaction, I would think she can be considered cat friendly. 

She has done very well on house training.  If taken outside at regular intervals, toileting will not be a problem.  I do crate her when she must be left alone, as she does have a tendency to chew on things when given the opportunity.  However, with proper exercise, chew toys and supervision, that will be less of a problem, especially as she outgrows her puppy ways.

Dixie does need daily exercise, including long walks and the ability to run and play.  A secure fenced in area would be a great help.  She is very good on a leash and looks forward to her daily walks.  Also, she does well riding in the car.

I do not crate her at night, and she does fine sleeping in her bed in my bedroom, although she would love to be invited as a bed partner.

She knows basic commands and seems to be a quick learner.  She loves my dog and plays well with him, even insisting on sleeping with him at night.  I separate the dogs during feeding, but she shows no signs of being food or toy aggressive. 

Dixie has a good temperament and will make a wonderful companion for someone who has the time and ability to spend time with her and give her the exercise and attention she needs.  All she needs is a loving home.”

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Steve and time sure flew by. While waiting for my forever home I have technically become a senior citizen. No worse for wear though. I am still young at heart and active. Here is my story.. To say I am lucky to be here is an understatement. I was hit by a car and then left outside a shelter where I was put on a list to be euthanized. A very kind lady saw my story on Facebook and rescued me. I had surgery to fix my broken leg but I was left with a bit of nerve damage on another leg. My lower incisors are missing so I may have been chained and tried to chew through. Yes I had a horrible and tragic start to my life, but us dogs are amazing and resilient! I am the sweetest and friendliest boy you may ever meet. I was left with just a limp but I am happy and healthy and grateful to get a chance to find a wonderful forever home where I will be safe and loved! I get along with everyone.. people, dogs and maybe even cats. I am a medium size Lab mix and weigh about 30 lbs. I am about 7 years old and just a good natured boy.

Please know that it can be scary for an old fella to move into a new home. Just a little patience and tenderness until I feel safe and loved would be wonderful!

Size: Large (50-55lbs)

Gender: Spayed Female

Hi all! My name is Smuckers. Have you ever tasted Raspberry Jam? If you have then you will know why I got my name as Smuckers jam is super sweet, just like me! I came into care with the good folks at MUR along with my two pups- Jif and Skippy. They have been adopted into wonderful homes and now it's my turn to find a place to call my own. 

I have been learning a lot of things with my foster family. I am fully house and crate trained. I'm not a huge fan of little humans as they can make me uneasy, so a home with no kids under 16 is a must for me. I'm good with cats inside my home but when I'm outside small animals are pretty exciting for me so I need someone to help me learn to leave them alone. I am pretty good at walking on a leash but sometimes need to be reminded about leash manners. But I can be easily redirected with treats if I get too excited. I would also like to take some more classes with you so we can learn and grow together! Maybe a reactive class would be good so we can both learn how to redirect if something gets me overly excited. 

I know sit, stay, down, leave it and even shake. Shake comes in handy when you like swimming as much as me so I don’t shake at the wrong time and get everyone wet. I appreciate being introduced slowly to canine companions, so that I don’t get overwhelmed with our first hello. 

I do love a good bone to chew on; there is nothing quite like it. Foster mom says I am gentle but also curious, which I am told is a great combination. I do have some allergies, both food and environmental, so I am on a strict hypoallergenic diet. I need my new family to make sure they keep watch so I don’t get a flare up and we can catch it quickly! 

If you are looking for the perfect companion to warm your feet while you relax, I am the perfect gal for you. 

I have completed the following classes: 
Basic Obedience with Pliant Pack Positive Dog Training 
Impulse Control with Pliant Pack Positive Dog Training 
Reactive K9 with Pliant Pack Positive Dog Training 

PLEASE NOTE: Because we do not have a public shelter, an adoption application must be filled out in order to be approved to meet any of our animals available for adoption. No exceptions. Serious inquiries only.

animal.description: I AM aLIKI and I am AvAiLaBLE for AdOPtIOn I just turned 7 and am a 60 lb. male husky mix. My original owner had me since I was a pup but turned me into the Baldwin Park shelter during the 2019 holidays because I am epileptic. I get grand mal seizures. I was freed by Shadow Husky Rescue, Inc. on January 4, 2020. I went to the emergency vet three times this year, in March, June and October 2020. Finally, the proper dosage of phenobarbital was figured out plus I take keppra, potassium bromide and milk thistle daily. I need a savior to help me if I ever feel vulnerable and experience a seizure again. I cannot survive without proper oversight and treatment. When I get a grand mal seizure, my whole body gets rigid and my head and lips get thrown back, my teeth are exposed, my legs are flailing around and I drool a lot of saliva. I usually chatter my jaws. It really helps when I get ocular compression to stimulate my vagus nerve to help redirect the electrical stuff in my brain so I can come out of it quicker. My head weaves a little bit while I am upright lying down. It’s a really icky feeling. I enjoy being held and told everything is going to be all right, getting iced down or having a bath towel soaked in cold water placed around my belly, chest and back of neck. Then, I get yummy ice cream to raise my blood sugar, and extra protein because I burn calories when I shake. I hate crates and confined spaces. I also feel hungry all of the time due to the pheno so keep me out of the kitchen. Haha! I am good with other dogs but laid back and low key. I love to prance and follow my humans. I LOVE belly rubs. I never get separation anxiety with other furry friends or a human at home. I love stuffed animals, especially ones that squeak. I love to fetch balls and bring them back. I get along with cats. I love walks and walk so easily on a leash. I don’t like dog parks, but dogs can come to my home or I like to go places like the river. I need to find ??MY 4-eVEr hO?me ??. Other furry animals at home are great but not a necessity. P.S. I love you, Aliki We recently obtained the results of Aliki's DNA breed test.  He is 71% Siberian Husky, 16.5% GErman Shepherd Dog a nd 12.5% Chow Chow

AtLantis and her 6 puppies were rescued from Animal Control when they were 1 day old. They are all adopted out to great families and we are working on finding "mama's" perfect match.

She is a sweetheart with people and never has met a stranger to this day. She will play with other dogs if they are submissive and nonreactive when she meets them. However, if they bark at her, she is in protective mode and the fight is on.

Her favorite games are keep away and tug a war.  She loves to chase the ball if you keep a second one in your hand to entice her to drop the first one, ha!
She loves to play with older children. (they probably need to be at least 7 or 8 yrs old)

She is 48-49 lbs, 2-3 yrs old, and a shorty. She has not chewed up her toys or bed, neither has she dug in the yard. She does love to sneek my husband's garden gloves, though.

She sits and waits to pray before she eats. 
She would do best with a family that has a fenced yard.

Coco is a young playful mixed breed. She has a BEAUTIFUL coat!! She loves to go on walks and runs around the rescue. She also enjoys playing with her toys. She has lots of energy and would love a home with an active person to take her on walks, hikes and runs- or even someone just to play fetch with her in the yard every day. She is not a fan of other dogs but has been in a foster home with a cat and did just fine.  She was born in June of 2014. Come meet her at our rescue center today!

If you are interested in adopting, please complete our Pre-application: https://form.jotform.us/asr628/ShortAdoptionInquiry

----------------------PLEASE READ-------------------------------
Our dogs are dogs are fostered in Texas but available for adoption in the Pacific Northwest...With stops in - Lacey, WA  and Portland, OR.
These dogs are transported to a predetermined location agreed upon by the rescue.

Our out of state adoption fee is $400. This fee includes spay/neuter, current vaccinations, a registered microchip, a negative heartworm test, health certificate, and transport costs. 
As an Apollo direct adoption, the adoption interview/meet and greet occurs on video call (Skype, FB Messenger call, Facetime, etc). The adoption application and fee would be finalized prior to transport.

animal.description:
C really is for Cookie! This 4 year old brindle sprinkled princess is as sweet as her name suggests!  Cookie is house broken, dog friendly, and super sweet

Cookie is a perfect lady in the home and rarely barks. While she is currently in the city and well behaved in the apartment, Cookie asks for her future home to be in a suburban area or home with a yard. Sadly, the city life can be a bit overwhelming for her.

We hope her future home can help her learn to be the best leash walker she can be! She can get scared and nervous outside, which makes her harder to walk. In the yard, she will frolic, roll around, and play! It looks like our Cookie monster his the jackpot when she is able to stretch those legs. She would love to have a canine sibling, human siblings, or anyone to love her!

Sadly, Cookie was surrendered to the shelter after her family moved away. She was adopted from there and her adopter is facing hardships beyond her control. In Cookies best interest, she made the painful and selfless decision to surrender her to us in order for Cookie to have the home and attention she desperately needs.

If interested in adopting or fostering, please email us at twentypawsrescue@gmail.com or info@twentypawsrescue.com. Please note we respond to all emails. If you do not hear back from us, please follow up! Sometimes, emails get lost in cyberspace.

animal.description:
Piggy Pie is a velvet hippo, piglet, koala bear, trex, alligator, pittie girl that joined our medical foster care program July 2020! She is a show stopping little gray brindle American bully 50lb girl, about 6 years old, and rescued as a ‘stray’ from the city shelter. This snorting (and snoring wonder) came to us with skin infections ravaging every part of her. You touch her, hair (where there was hair) would fall out. Her skin was scaly, peeling, red, hot, and painful. Her paws were covered, top and bottom, with painful overfilled blisters. This impaired her ability to walk, since any surface was painful. Her ears were filled with fluid, neck inflamed, and still lactating. Someone used Piggy Pie as a breeding machine, took her puppies, and left her out in the streets. They were sore, red, hot, and swollen. The one thing that was unharmed, her spirit. Piggy Pie LOVES to love! 

After spending about 4 months in medical foster care healing from her past, she is ready for her forever home and to officially enter retirement from being used as a breeder dog. Graduation is a beautiful thing! Unfortunately, we don't know the fate of her puppies, but we can assure Piggy that there will never be heartache in her life again. In medical foster care, she received round the clock care for her medical conditions. Twice a day, Piggy takes several pills and has her ears cleaned. Every other day, Piggy Pie gets a medicated bath/massage. Her routine is complete with lots of naps, love, snoring, and cuddles with her foster siblings. Piggy Pie required regular check-ins to monitor her progress and rest. While in our foster home, Piggy Pie is enjoying training to work through her trauma and learn basic obedience! 

Piggy Pie is incredibly affectionate, loving, and the funniest girl you will ever meet, with the chubbiest little paws. When she pouts, she will stick her head between her paws, show her little underbite, and pout her bottom lip! While she loves people, and is very respectful around children, she does ask to be the only pet in the home. She can get along with other dogs, but she rarely takes no for an answer from other dogs and can easily get too sassy for a situation. For this, we nicknamed her Piggy 'No Neck'.

Our little gangster is crate trained, housebroken, fantastic in the car, and is happy to share her toys with her humans. She loves toys! Much in line with the fingerfood pigs in a blanket, Piggy Pie loves to be rolled up and nuzzled in a blanket for bed or naptime. She will gladly snooze the day away curled into your side, neck, or hip- while hugging you! Just as much, she is happy snoring in her bed on her own.

We must warn you, the noises this Piggy Pie makes are like no other! Adopt her and you might think you adopted some new barn yard animals! No worries, though, this is just her- a koala piglet crossed with an alligators self.  
Piggy's former skin infections left her with scars on her chin. The person that adopts her MUST be prepared to give her a medicated bath twice a week and clean her paws and chin twice a day with a special solution. Skipping a bath or wipe results in a flare up!

If interested in adopting, please email us at twentypawsrescue@gmail.com or info@twentypawsrescue.com. Please note we respond to all emails. If you do not hear back from us, please follow up! Sometimes, emails get lost in cyberspace.
